e, 1945.jpg|266px]]\n| caption    = Ethnic Chinese in traditional ''[[cheongsam]]'' attire with [[umbrella]], {{circa|1945}}.\n| population = '''6,642,000'''{{sfn|Department of Information Malaysia|2015}}<br />'''23.4%''' of the Malaysian population (2016){{sfn|Department of Statistics Malaysia|2016}}\n| popplace   = '''{{Flag|Malaysia}}'''<br />[[Penangite Chinese|Penang]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Johor]], [[Perak]], [[Selangor]], [[Sarawak]]<br />'''{{Flag|Australia}}'''<br />[[Christmas Island]]{{sfn|Department of Infrastructure and Regional Development Australia|2016|p=2}}<br />'''{{flag|Singapore}}''' (338,501 in 2010){{sfn|Department of Statistics Singapore|2010|p=31}}<br />'''{{Flag|New Zealand}}'''{{NoteTag|Of the 8,820 Malaysian-born people resident in [[New Zealand]] in 1991, only 1,383 were [[Malaysian Malay|Malay]]; most of the rest were Chinese Malaysians. In the [[2013 New Zealand census]], 16,350 people were born in Malaysia. Of these, more than five-eighths gave their ethnicity as Chinese or Malaysian Chinese. The next most numerous were Malays, with smaller groups of [[Malaysian Indians|Indians]] and other [[Asian people]]s.{{sfn|Walrond|2015}}}}\n| langs      = [[Malaysian Mandarin|Mandarin]] (lingua franca), [[Malaysian language|Malaysian]] (national language), [[Malaysian English|English]]<br />''Mothertongue languages'': [[Hokkien]], [[Cantonese]], [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]], [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]], [[Fuzhou dialect|Foochow]], [[Hainanese]], [[Taishanese]] and [[Puxian dialect|Henghua]]; [[Manglish]] (creole)\n| rels       = Predominantly [[Mahayana|Mah\u0101y\u0101na Buddhism]] and [[Taoism]] ([[Chinese folk religion]]), significant [[Christianity]], minorities [[Islam]] and [[Hinduism]]\n| related    = [[Ethnic Chinese in Brunei|Bruneian Chinese]]{{\u00b7}}[[Chinese Singaporeans|Singaporean Chinese]]{{\u00b7}}[[Chinese Indonesians|Indonesian Chinese]]{{\u00b7}}[[Thai Chinese]]{{\u00b7}}[[Peranakan]]{{\u00b7}}[[Overseas Chinese]]\n}}\n{{Chinese\n| t   = {{linktext|\u99ac\u4f86\u897f\u4e9e|\u83ef\u4eba|lang=zh}}\n| s   = {{linktext|\u9a6c\u6765\u897f\u4e9a|\u534e\u4eba|lang=zh}}\n| p   = M\u01cel\u00e1ix\u012by\u00e0 Hu\u00e1r\u00e9n\n| w   = Ma\u00b3-lai\u00b2-hsi\u00b9-ya\u2074 Hua\u00b2-j\u00ean\u00b2\n| tp  = M\u01ce-l\u00e1i-xi-y\u00e0 Hu\u00e1-r\u00e9n\n| mi  = {{IPA-cmn|m\u00e0l\u01cei\u0255\u00edj\u00e2 xw\u01ce\u027b\u0259\u030cn|}}\n| j   = Maa<sup>5</sup> loi<sup>1</sup> sai<sup>1</sup> aa<sup>3</sup> Waa<sup>1</sup> jan<sup>1</sup>\n| y   = M\u00e1hl\u00f2is\u0101ia W\u00e0y\u00e0n\n| gd  = Ma<sup>5</sup> loi<sup>1</sup> sei<sup>1</sup> a<sup>3</sup> Wa<sup>1</sup> yen<sup>1</sup>\n| ci  = {{IPA-yue|ma\u032c\u02d0l\u0254\u0301\u02d0ys\u0250\u0301i.\u0101\u02d0 w\u00e1\u02d0.j\u0250\u0301n|}}\n| t2  = {{linktext|\u99ac\u4f86\u897f\u4e9e|\u83ef\u50d1|lang=zh}}\n| s2  = {{linktext|\u9a6c\u6765\u897f\u4e9a|\u534e\u4fa8|lang=zh}}\n| p2  = M\u01cel\u00e1ix\u012by\u00e0 Hu\u00e1qi\u00e1o\n| w2  = Ma\u00b3-lai\u00b2-hsi\u00b9-ya\u2074 Hua\u00b2-ch'iao\u00b2\n| tp2 = M\u01ce-l\u00e1i-xi-y\u00e0 Hu\u00e1-ci\u00e1o\n| mi2 = {{IPA-cmn|m\u00e0l\u01cei\u0255\u00edj\u00e2 xw\u01ce.t\u0255\u02b0j\u01ceu|}}\n| j2  = Maa<sup>5</sup> loi<sup>1</sup> sai<sup>1</sup> aa<sup>3</sup> Waa<sup>1</sup> kiu<sup>1</sup>\n| y2  = M\u00e1hl\u00f2is\u0101ia W\u00e0ki\u00f9\n| gd2 = Ma<sup>5</sup> loi<sup>1</sup> sei<sup>1</sup> a<sup>3</sup> Wa<sup>1</sup> kiu<sup>1</sup>\n| ci2 = {{IPA-yue|ma\u032c\u02d0l\u0254\u0301\u02d0ys\u0250\u0301i.\u0101\u02d0 w\u00e1\u02d0.k\u02b0i\u02d0\u00fa|}}\n| t3 = {{linktext|\u99ac\u4f86\u897f\u4e9e|\u5510\u4eba|lang=zh}}\n| poj3 = Ma-l\u00e0i-s\u00e8-a T\u01f9g-L\u00e1ng\n| y3 = M\u00e1hl\u00f2is\u0101ia T\u00f2hngy\u00e0hn\n}}\n\n'''Malaysian Chinese people''' or '''Chinese Malaysians''' ({{lang-zh|\u9a6c\u6765\u897f\u4e9a\u534e\u4eba}}; {{lang-ms|Orang Cina Malaysia}}) is a local ethnic group in Malaysia. The group is defined as local [[Malaysians]] of ethnic [[Chinese people|Chinese]] ([[Han Chinese]]) ancestry. Today, they form the second largest ethnic group after the Malay majority. Most are descendants of [[South China|Southern Chinese]] immigrants who arrived in Malaysia between the early 19th century and the mid-20th century.\n\nThe sub-ethnic groups of Malaysian Chinese includes [[Hoklo people|Hokkien]], [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]], [[Hakka people|Hakka]], [[Teochew people|Teochew]], [[Hainan people|Hainan]], [[Fuzhou people|Foochow]] and [[Kwongsai people|Kwongsai]]. Malaysian Chinese also form the second largest community of [[Overseas Chinese]] in the world, after [[Thai Chinese]]. Within Malaysia, they represent the third largest group, constituting 23% of the Malaysian population.\n\nMalaysian Chinese are traditionally dominant in the business sector of the [[Economy of Malaysia|Malaysian economy]]. Different towns and cities in Malaysia are placed by different Chinese dialects among Chinese speakers; for example [[Cantonese]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Ipoh]] and [[Sandakan]], [[Hokkien]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], [[Klang (city)|Klang]] and [[Kuching]], [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]] in [[Kota Kinabalu]], [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]] in [[Johor Bahru]], [[Fuzhou dialect|Foochow]] in [[Sibu]], [[Miri]] and [[Sitiawan]], and [[Hainanese]] in [[Kuala Terengganu]].{{sfn|Gabacc\u00eda|Hoerder|2011|p=218}} But, [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]] is now widely used as a [[working language]] or lingua franca among the different Chinese ethnicities and younger generations.\n\nCulturally, most Malaysian Chinese have maintained their Chinese heritage, including their various dialects, although the descendants of the earliest Chinese migrants who arrived from the 13th to 17th centuries have assimilated aspects of the Malay or indigenous cultures, where they form a distinct sub-ethnic group known as the [[Peranakan]]s in [[Kelantan]] and [[Terengganu]], Baba-Nyonya in [[Malacca]] and [[Penang]] as well the Sino-Natives in [[Sabah]]. Malaysian Chinese are usually referred to simply as \"Chinese\" in Malaysia, \"''Orang Cina''\" in [[Malay language|Malay]], \"''Sina''\" or \"''Kina''\" among [[Bornean languages|Borneo]] indigenous, \"''C\u012b\u1e49ar''\" ({{lang|ta|\u0b9a\u0bc0\u0ba9\u0bb0\u0bcd}}) in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and  \"''[[Huaxia|Huaren]]''\" ({{lang|zh-Hant|\u83ef\u4eba}}, Chinese people) or \"''Huaqiao''\" ({{lang|zh-Hant|\u83ef\u50d1}}, Overseas Chinese) by local Chinese themselves.\n\nEven with absolute population numbers increasing with each censuses, the proportion of ethnic Chinese among the country's total population has been consistently declining, partially due to a lower [[birth rate]] as well as a high level of [[emigration]] in recent decades. According to a report by the [[World Bank]], the [[Malaysian diaspora]] around the world in 2010 numbered at around a million, most of them ethnic Chinese. The main reasons for emigrating are the better economic and career prospects abroad and a sense of social injustice within Malaysia.{{sfn|World Bank|2011|p=12}} The large number of emigrants, many of whom are young and highly educated, constitute a significant \"[[human capital flight|brain drain]]\" from the country, especially to nearby Singapore.<ref>{{harvnb|Defillippi|Arthur|Lindsay|2009|p=117}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Fong|Zubair|2017|p=15}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Jakobsen|2014|p=170}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Tyson|2018|p=55}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{see also|History of Malaysia}}\n\n=== Early history ===\n[[File:Chinese junk in Kinabatangan, Borneo.JPG|thumb|left|The presence of Chinese [[junk (ship)|junk]] in northern [[Borneo]] on [[Kinabatangan District|Kinabatangan]] as photographed by [[Martin and Osa Johnson]], {{circa|1935}}.]]\nSince the [[History of China|early dynasties of China]], there has been connection between China and various early kingdoms in the [[Malay Archipelago]], such as in the northern area of [[Malay Peninsula]] and Po-Ni in the western part of [[Borneo]].<ref>{{harvnb|Andaya|1982|p=17}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Zepp|1989|pp=19\u201321}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Wong|1999|p=132}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Munoz|2006|p=178}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Lee|2013|p=542}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Wan|Mair|Roberts|Swofford|2013|pp=7\u201311}}</ref> The first recorded movement of people from [[Yuan dynasty|China]] into the present-territory of Malaysia was during the arrival of [[Mongol Empire|Mongol]] expeditionary forces under the led of [[Kublai Khan]] to Borneo in 1292 for their preparation in the [[Mongol invasion of Java|invasion of Java]] in 1293.{{sfn|Royal Society (Great Britain)|1924|p=157}}{{sfn|Runciman|2011|p=11}} Many of his Chinese followers and traders later settled and established their own enclave within the [[Kinabatangan River]] as a result of the campaign with their arrival are warmly received by the [[indigenous people]] in the island who were eager to possess the [[jar]]s and [[bead]] they brought along with [[silk]]s, metalwork and [[Chinese ceramics|pottery]].{{sfn|Wong|1998|p=2}}{{sfn|Guillot|Lombard|Ptak|1998|p=162}}{{sfn|Runciman|2011|p=14}}\n\n[[File:Map of Ming Chinese empire 1415.jpg|thumb|right|Map of [[Ming dynasty]] under [[Yongle Emperor]] in the year of 1415, map published in 1935.]]\nThrough the establishment of firm relationship, a Chinese explorer and mariner named [[Zheng He]] commanded [[Ming treasure voyages|several expeditions to southeastern Asia]] between 1405 and 1430 where they visiting [[Malacca Sultanate|Malacca]] in their third voyage.{{sfn|Brezina|2016|p=58}} His accompanier and translator named [[Ma Huan]] described the place in his ''[[Yingya Shenglan]]'' as formerly under Siam before a local king there asserting for independence to become an \"Islamised country\", and by the time of their fourth imperial fleet visit, he described the local king had just [[religious conversion|converted]] and dressed like an [[Arab people|Arab]] with his kingdom are chafing under the Chinese dominance.{{sfn|Ma|Huan|Feng|1970|p=109}}{{sfn|Gordon|2007|p=133}} The last edition of official Chinese historical works of ''[[Twenty-Four Histories]]'' named as [[History of Ming]] (''Mingshi'') made a brief mention of an already established Chinese settlement in the area,{{sfn|Tan|1988|p=29}} followed by other records especially when trade contacts had been established with the [[Nanyang (region)|Nanyang]] region.{{sfn|Purcell|1947|p=115\u2013125}} The ''Words about the Sea'' (Hai Y\u00fc) written by Hwang Chung (Huang Zhong) and published in 1537 gives further account on the life practice of the Chinese community in Malacca which are different than the local [[Ethnic Malays|Malays]].{{sfn|Groeneveldt|1876|p=7}}\n\nThe connection is well maintained even with the Islamisation of the Malacca and [[Bruneian Empire|Brunei]] kingdoms, whose [[thalassocracy]] once covered much of the territory of the present-day Malaysia.  Both of the Muslim sultanates pledged protection from the Chinese dynasties to shield them from further conquest either by neighbouring Javanese [[Majapahit]] or Siamese [[Ayutthaya Kingdom|Ayutthaya]].{{sfn|Cohen|2000|p=175}}{{sfn|Ma|Cartier|2003|p=79}}{{sfn|de Vienne|2015|p=42\u201343}} The close relationship also resulted in the [[interracial marriage]] between the Sultanate royal family and Chinese envoy and representatives.{{sfn|Ma|Cartier|2003|p=90}}{{sfn|Lee|2010|p=11}}{{sfn|Ooi|2015|p=50}} Zheng He's arrival propagated the [[Islam in Southeast Asia|spread of Islam in the Malay Archipelago]] and aided the growth of [[Hui people|Chinese Muslim]] population from the eastern China's coastal towns of [[Fujian]] and [[Guangzhou|Canton]] with many of their traders arrived at the coastal towns of present-day Malaysia and [[Indonesia]] by the early 15th century.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=115}}{{sfn|Ma|2017|p=11}} Apart from the early settlements in Kinabatangan and Malacca, two other oldest Chinese settlements are located in [[Terengganu]] and [[Penang Island]] as part of the trade networks with the respective areas.{{sfn|Lee|1965|p=306\u2013314}}{{sfn|Wong|2016|p=9\u201321}}{{sfn|Wade|Chin|2018|p=249}}\n\n=== Colonial era (1500\u20131900) ===\n[[File:Bukit Chena, Malacca (7886253620).jpg|thumb|left|[[Bukit Cina]] (literally \"Chinese Hill\") in [[Malacca Sultanate|Malacca]], one of the oldest Chinese cemetery in the country, taken between {{circa|1860\u20131900}}.{{sfn|Wong|2016|p=9\u201321}}]]\nFollowing the [[Capture of Malacca (1511)|conquest of Malacca]] by the [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese]] in 1511, many Chinese traders avoided [[Portuguese Malacca]] although the flow of emigrants from China continued.{{sfn|Guillot|Lombard|Ptak|1998|p=179}}\nThe [[Zhengde Emperor]] conducted several retaliations against the Portuguese due to their activities in Malacca during the [[Ming dynasty]], following the arrival of her fleet in Canton.{{sfn|Zhang|1934|p=67}} However, the Chinese emperor was reluctant to help the deposed Malaccan ruler reclaim his position, as the dynasty{{'s}} foreign policy was being changed to maintain friendly relations with the Portuguese.{{sfn|Zhang|1934|p=67}}{{sfn|Wade|Chin|2018|p=144}}\n\nHis successor, the [[Jiajing Emperor]] later changed the attitude of the Ming court by executing two government officials and reaffirming the importance of issues regarding the Malacca in major policy decisions.{{sfn|Wade|Chin|2018|p=144}} Regardless, some Chinese from China proper, including those from Fujian, defying Ming dynasty regulation for the sake of trade, informed the Portuguese on the trade route between [[Guangdong]] and Siam. The local Malaccan Chinese were not treated favourably by the Portuguese, so they, along with most overseas Chinese, refused to cooperate with the Portuguese.<ref>{{harvnb|Guillot|Lombard|Ptak|1998|p=179}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Wernham|1968|p=543}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Kratoska|2001a|p=101}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Borschberg|2004|p=12}}</ref> Through the administration of Portuguese in Malacca, Chinese Muslims sided with other Islamic traders against the latter by providing ships and [[human capital|capital]].{{sfn|Borschberg|2004|p=12}} A negotiation was later held in Guangdong regarding the Malaccan issues between the Chinese officials and Portuguese envoys, with Malacca remaining under Portuguese control.{{sfn|Wade|Chin|2018|p=145\u2013146}}\n[[File:Malaysia; Captain China surrounded by his Chinese and Malay Wellcome V0037516.jpg|thumb|right|Chinese [[secret society]] of [[Hai San Secret Society|Hai San]] with Chinese and [[Ethnic Malays|Malay]] followers in [[Selangor Sultanate|Selangor]], {{circa|1874}}.]]\nFollowing the [[Dutch Empire|Dutch]] [[Battle of Malacca (1641)|takeover of Malacca]] in 1641,{{sfn|Bluss\u00e9|2009|p=23}} many local Malaccan Chinese were hired for the construction of Dutch buildings.{{sfn|Lim|Fernando|2006|p=126}} The Dutch found the Chinese to be industrious and encouraged the latter{{'s}} participation in the economic life of the Dutch colony.{{sfn|Ramanathan|1994|p=67}} Under their administration, the Dutch also established a settlement in [[Perak Sultanate|Perak]] in 1650 through an earlier treaty with [[Aceh Sultanate|Aceh]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=479}} The Dutch further suggested the 17th Sultan of Perak, Alauddin, to allow the Chinese to develop [[tin mining|tin mines]], which was warmly welcomed by the latter. It also facilitated his scheme of requesting more Chinese workers to be sent from Malacca. He promised to punish any official guilty of mistreating the Chinese as well.{{sfn|Khoo|Lubis|2005|p=5}}{{sfn|anon.|2014|p=210}}\n\nWith the Sultan{{'s}} consent, the Chinese began playing a leading role in the industry; however, as a result of the [[Fourth Anglo-Dutch War]] in 1780, tin trade was adversely affected and many Chinese miners left.{{sfn|Khoo|1972|p=39}} Despite the existence of early Chinese settlements in Malacca and several areas along the coasts of the archipelago, the mass migration of Chinese to Malaysia largely occurred after the opening of British settlements in both [[British Malaya]] and [[British Borneo]] during the early 19th century.{{sfn|Hirschman|1986|p=338}}\n[[File:British officials in Perak with wealthy Chinese person.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Wealthy Chinese person with British colonial officials in [[Perak Sultanate|Perak]], {{circa|1904}}.]]\nThe opening of a British settlement in Penang (1786) and another in [[Founding of modern Singapore|Singapore]] (1819) triggered an emigration from China to the Malay Peninsula.{{sfn|Hirschman|1986|p=338}} Following the establishment of British rule in [[Crown Colony of Labuan|Labuan]] in 1846, more ethnic Chinese, the majority of whom are [[Hakka people|Hakka]] and many of them from Singapore, arrived at the British Borneo part of [[North Borneo]]. The migration trend continued through the first few years of the establishment of the [[North Borneo Chartered Company]].{{sfn|Wong|1999|p=132}}\nChinese migration to both Labuan and North Borneo is largely confined to the [[agricultural]] sectors, while in the [[Raj of Sarawak]], they are largely restricted to the mining, as well as the agricultural sectors.{{sfn|Geography of British Colonies|1864|p=31}}{{sfn|Niew|1969|p=2}} Rajah [[Charles Brooke, Rajah of Sarawak|Charles Brooke]] of Sarawak promoted the migration of the Chinese, along with the [[Dayak people|Dayak]], to the interior of Sarawak in order to develop the area. This resulted in the establishment of an administrative centre and a trading centre (''[[bazaar]]'') by the 19th century, primarily in the First, Second and Third Divisions of the country.{{sfn|Drabble|2000|p=86}}\n\nIn 1876, Rajah Charles further invited Chinese-[[black pepper|pepper]] grower from Singapore to settle in Kuching, which later being joined by local Chinese miners and others from neighbouring Dutch Borneo.{{sfn|Gurney|1986|p=268}}{{sfn|Bulbeck|Reid|Tan|Yiqi|1998|p=68}} With the introduction of pepper into the kingdom, the entire pepper cultivation in Sarawak area of Kuching-Serian in the First Division are dominated by the Hakka, while the [[Fuzhou people|Foochow]] and [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] dominate the cultivation in Sarikei-Binatang area in the Third Division, making Sarawak the second largest pepper producer in the world.{{sfn|Bulbeck|Reid|Tan|Yiqi|1998|p=68}}{{sfn|Kaur|2016|p=48}} Following the British success in gaining direct control on the four states of Perak, [[Selangor Sultanate|Selangor]], [[Yamtuan Besar|Negeri Sembilan]] and [[Sultan of Pahang|Pahang]], nearly two million Chinese immigrants entered with half of 1.5 million in both Perak and Selangor.{{sfn|Doran|Dixon|1991|p=111}}{{sfn|Kratoska|2001b|p=209}}\n\n[[File:The National geographic magazine (Page 164) BHL40563162 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Children are being [[pulled rickshaw|pulled]] by a Chinese [[coolie]] through the streets of [[Kuching]] in the [[Raj of Sarawak]], {{circa|1919}}.]]\n\nWith the [[tin sources and trade in ancient times|further discovery of rich tin deposits]] in British Malaya, the Chinese immigrants became more involved in the tin mining businesses with many of their labourers work in the industry.{{sfn|Yat|1969|p=57}} With more tin mines opened in Perak, many of the Chinese community in neighbouring Penang also gain profits and become wealthy.{{sfn|Douw|Huang|Ip|2013|p=165}} By the 1870s, many Chinese tin mining communities had been established in the Malay Peninsula, particularly in [[Ipoh]] ([[Kinta Valley]]), [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]],\n[[Seremban]] and [[Kuala Lumpur]] ([[Klang Valley]]) which is largely dominated by Hakka and Cantonese group.{{sfn|Tin Industry (Research and Development) Board|1955|p=9}}{{sfn|Lin|Hill|1979|p=145}} Each of the mining communities were governed by a [[Kapitan Cina]] with duties and privileges similar as being used in the ''[[Kangchu system]]'' of [[Johor Sultanate|Johor]].{{sfn|Landa|2016|p=58}} The huge influx of Chinese migration are directly caused by the poverty in rural China and massive employment opportunities in the British colonial or [[protectorate]] territories with an estimated of 5 million Chinese had entered by the 19th century and 12 million more despite a total of 17 million later either moved to other parts of Southeast Asia or return to China.{{sfn|Ching|McKenna|1990|p=2}} Nonetheless with their economic success following the migration, there were also disorder among the Chinese communities as they were divided into different [[secret societies]] which in part exarcerbated by political unrest among Malay aristocracy fighting for the right to be chief with each side enlisting help from different Chinese secret societies faction.{{sfn|Landa|2016|p=58}}{{sfn|Comber|1956|p=146\u2013162}} The situation of the local Malay politics at the time are described by observers as plagued with anarchy and civil war between their own kind, prompting alliances of high placed Malay political leaders with the Chinese as well European officials for protection and securing their investments.{{sfn|Peletz|1996|p=102}}\n\n=== Divided nationalism and turbulent era (1900\u20131945) ===\n{{See also|Chinese revolutionary activities in Malaya}}\n\n{{quote box\n| quote  = You can help shoulder the responsibility of saving our country by donating your money, while our comrades in our country are sacrificing their lives.\n| width  = 25%\n| align  = left\n| source = &nbsp;\u2014[[Sun Yat-sen]], during his speech at the [[1910 Penang conference]] in the [[Straits Settlements]] of Penang.{{sfn|Khoo|2008|p=55}}\n}}\n[[File:Fundraising in Ipoh for the Second Guangzhou uprising.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Tongmenghui]] fundraising meeting in [[Ipoh]] of Perak for the [[Second Guangzhou uprising]], {{circa|1911}}.]]\n\nBy the 1900s, civil wars and conflicts between the indigenous ethnics began to cease when the British established firm control over both Malaya and northern Borneo despite none of the Malay kingdoms was actually colonised with all the related entities came under political and economic stability as well economic prosperity under the British [[capital (economics)|capital]] and economic geared up by the Chinese and Indian workforce through the national exploitation of tin and [[natural rubber|rubber]].{{sfn|Ching|McKenna|1990|p=2}}{{sfn|Khoo|2010}} Prior to the [[Xinhai Revolution|1911 Chinese Revolution]] that successfully overthrow the [[Qing dynasty]] in China, the leader of the [[Tongmenghui]] revolt named [[Sun Yat-sen]] raise overseas funding and organisational support from overseas Chinese communities mainly from [[French Indochina]], [[Dutch East Indies]], [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippines]], [[Rattanakosin Kingdom (1782\u20131932)|Siam]], British Singapore, British Malaya and British Borneo with the establishment of Nanyang revolutionary organisation activities in [[Saigon]], [[Hanoi]], [[Pontianak, Indonesia|Pontianak]], [[Manila]], [[Bangkok]], Singapore and [[George Town, Penang|George Town]].<ref>{{harvnb|de Ruff\u00e9|1928|p=124}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Harris|1956|p=98}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Png|1961|pp=1\u201332}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Journal of the Siam Society|1974|p=44}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Suryadinata|2006|p=122}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Lai|Lee|2011|p=247}}</ref> Through the way to transform the current administration of China, a competition raise between three groups who champion the political reformation with each of the group targeted overseas Chinese especially in Malaya and Singapore for their source of support and funds.{{sfn|Khoo|2008|p=24}} The first group consists of the pro-Qing elite, who mainly targets wealthy Chinese for funds and expertise to modernise China, while the other two are reformists and revolutionaries who intends to advocated [[constitutional amendment|constitutional reforms]], introduction of [[parliamentary system]] and complete overthrow of Qing and Manchu political influence for a modern Chinese nation.{{sfn|Khoo|2008|p=24}}\n\n[[File:Three Chinese girls working at the British mobile canteen in Malaya.JPG|thumb|260px|left|Three ethnic Chinese girls working in the interior of British military [[mobile canteen]] throughout the [[Malayan Campaign|war against the Japanese]] in Malaya, {{circa|January 1942}}.]]\nFollowing the success of reformists and revolutionaries after the revolution with the establishment of a new Chinese government under the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]], many branches of the Tongmenghui succeeding party of [[Kuomintang]] emerged in British Malaya with majority support were first shown by Straits-born Chinese than the China-born.{{sfn|Khoo|2010}} In British Borneo, Kuomintang activities came under the Democratic Party of North Borneo, a body formed by Chinese-educated [[:wikt:towkay|towkays]] despite it is not known whether China assisted the activities.{{sfn|Borneo Research Council|1977|p=114}} The patriotism among Chinese immigrant communities was then entirely focused on China.{{sfn|Wang|1964|p=141}} The British colonial authorities initially do not have problem for any Chinese residing in the two territories becoming Kuomintang members but with the [[anti-imperialism|anti-imperialists]] policy within the organisation, this resulted the British and the new China government unable to maintain a close relationship.{{sfn|Hak|2000|p=69}} By 1925, when a communist movement emerged among the overseas Chinese with the establishment of [[South Seas Communist Party]] in colonial Singapore and its subsequent banning, this further leading to the establishment of [[Indochinese Communist Party]], [[Communist Party of Malaya]], [[Communist Party of Burma]] and the [[Communist Party of Siam]] with the communist movement also maintaining relations with an earlier Southeast Asia [[Communist Party of Indonesia]].{{sfn|Kennedy|1957|p=213}}{{sfn|Hara|2016|p=12\u201313}} Prior to the [[World War II]], the Communist Party of Malaya followed the general communists line of opposing [[Liberal democracy|Western democracies]] by intensifying its propaganda against the Malayan government as well the colonial government of Singapore in 1940.{{sfn|Tay|2018}}\n\n[[File:The British Reoccupation of Malaya SE5883.jpg|thumb|right|Thousands of [[Malayan Peoples' Anti-Japanese Army]] (MPAJA) guerrillas with the majority come from the ethnic Chinese during their disbandment ceremony in [[Kuala Lumpur]] after the end of war against the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] in 1945.]]\nWith the beginning of Sino-Japanese conflict and subsequent Japanese occupations of [[Japanese occupation of Malaya|Malaya]] and [[Japanese occupation of British Borneo|British Borneo]], further activities by young Kuomintang enthusiasts were shortly stopped.{{sfn|Journal of South-East Asian History|1961|p=224}} When the [[Communist Party of China]] under [[Mao Zedong]] reached an agreement with the Kuomintang government under [[Chiang Kai-shek]] to put aside their conflict and rally together against Japanese aggression in July 1940, a growth of anti-British led to the banning of Kuomintang and other Chinese organisations in Malaya.{{sfn|Tay|2018}}{{sfn|Wang|1964|p=144}} Nevertheless, with the ensuing conflict with [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] that also involving the British, Chiang Kai-shek urge every Kuomintang members to fight alongside the latter with the British colonial authorities in return announced the lifting of ban towards any Chinese associations including both the Kuomintang and Chinese communist movement as a sign to appreciating the value of co-operation.{{sfn|Cheah|2013|p=37}} The leaving of ban and subsequent recognition by the British colonial authorities towards the Communist Party of Malaya as their ally resulted in the formation of the party [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla]] force of [[Malayan Peoples' Anti-Japanese Army]] (MPAJA) in 1941.{{sfn|Suryadinata|2012|p=136}} The MPAJA which consisted mainly of ethnic Chinese in Malaya waged a guerrilla war against the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] (IJA) throughout Malaya with the movement had a total strength of 10,000 men from eight battalions where they also made contact with the British [[Force 136]] during the war.{{sfn|Wong|2002a}} Some revolt by local Chinese under the influence of the Kuomintang such as the [[Jesselton revolt|Jesselton uprising]] in British Borneo occur through the Japanese harsh administration but as similarly happened towards many innocent civilians, they were severely repressed by Japanese secret police of [[Kenpeitai]].{{sfn|Thurman|Sherman|2001|p=123}}{{sfn|Tay|2016}}\n\nIn North Borneo, much of the underground anti-Japanese activities by ethnic Chinese is part of the Nanyang Chinese National Salvation Movement led by [[Tan Kah Kee]] while in Sarawak most of them operating under the communist-influenced movement of Sarawak Anti Fascist League.{{sfn|der Kroef|1964|p=50\u201360}}{{sfn|Wong|2001|p=93\u2013105}} The [[Pacific War|victory of the Allies in the Pacific]] in 1945 led to the disbandment of MPAJA guerrillas in the Malay Peninsula and many of their leading members receiving awards from the British.{{sfn|Hartfield|2012|p=350}} But even with the disbandment after the war ended, the MPAJA has adopted a radical policy and began to massacring those, mainly Malays who they had considered as collaborators during their war against the Japanese, causing a rising [[ethnic tension|ethnic conflict]] when the Malays began to retaliated.{{sfn|Kantowicz|2000|p=111}} The MPAJA also targeting British posts with several [[grenade]] attacks on British troops.{{sfn|Hartfield|2012|p=350}} Different situation happened in North Borneo which is under Kuomintang influence when ethnic Chinese there choose to co-operate with the British and being loyal to King [[George VI]] towards the formation of the [[Crown Colony of North Borneo]] after the war.{{sfn|Kalgoorlie Miner|1946}}\n\n=== Post-turbulent, further emergency and social integration (1946\u20131962) ===\n[[File:Police in Malayan Emergency.jpg|thumb|left|British and Malayan police talking to a Chinese civilian who may have information about any communist activities in their area, {{circa|1949}}.]]\n{{quote box\n| quote  = The answer [to the uprising] lies not in pouring more troops into the jungle, but in the hearts and minds of the people.\n| width  = 25%\n| align  = right\n| source = &nbsp;\u2014[[Gerald Templer]], following his appointment as [[List of High Commissioners of the United Kingdom to Malaya|British High Commissioner to Malaya]] to deal with [[Malayan Emergency]] in 1952.{{sfn|Lapping|1985|p=224}}\n}}\n\nWith the rebranding of MPAJA to [[Malayan National Liberation Army]] (MNLA), attacks by communist insurgents further ensued with their guerrilla tactics in the jungles by sabotaging transportation networks and attacking British plantation sources that resulted in the assassination of several European plantation owners in Malaya.{{sfn|Kantowicz|2000|p=111}} The British intelligence estimate the support for the MNLA was mainly based on around 500,000 from the total of 3.12 million ethnic Chinese living in Malaya by the time and battling the insurgents proved difficult as most of them hid in inaccessible jungles.{{sfn|David|Joe|2009}} With the declaration of emergency on 18 June 1948 during the ensuing [[Malayan Emergency]], the early government response was chaotic and disorganised as their primary target is only to guard important economic targets.{{sfn|Leifer|2013|p=110}}{{sfn|Ong|2014|p=87}} The predominantly nature of the MNLA which consisted entirely from ethnic Chinese making most of the Malays who constituted nearly half of the population of five million in 1950 opposed the movement.{{sfn|Hack|1999|p=99\u2013125}}\n\n[[File:New Village in Malaya, 1950s.jpg|thumb|right|Many government-controlled new village established in Malaya in the 1950s to segregated ethnic Chinese who have connection with communist insurgents.{{sfn|Yamada|2004|p=225\u2013231}}]]\n\nA military plan called [[Briggs' Plan]] which devised by British General [[Harold Rawdon Briggs|Harold Briggs]] are being undertaken shortly in 1950 to protect the population and isolate any connection of involved population from the insurgents which is also followed by the promise for independence, with the latter won majority support from the Malays although the Chinese population need more convincing as they feared on being treated as a \"second-class citizens\" in an independent Malaya.{{sfn|Chaliand|1982|p=272}} Among the steps being undertaken under the plan includes the establishment of rapid settlement of squatters under security surveillance, regrouping of labour, minimum level of troops throughout Malaya to support security forces on clearing priority areas and complete accord of operation between police and army with close integration of intelligence.{{sfn|Hamby|2002|p=59}} Under the continual resettlement scheme, more than 700,000 rural ethnic Chinese community were corralled into 582 new settlements established by the government around Malaya.{{sfn|Yamada|2004|p=225\u2013231}} With the demise of British colonial administrator [[Henry Gurney]] after a sudden ambush by the insurgents in 1951, [[Gerald Templer]] are appointed as a new colonial administrator to Malaya by [[Winston Churchill]] in the following year with the latter then primarily choose the \"[[winning hearts and minds|hearts and minds campaign]]\" apart from military and psychological measures to combat the insurgents.{{sfn|David|Joe|2009}}{{sfn|Stubbs|2004|p=1}}{{sfn|Ramakrishna|2013|p=139}} As part of his campaign, Templer instituted incentive schemes for surrendering rebels including to those who encouraged them to surrender and used strict [[curfew]]s and tight control of food supplies from involved areas to flush out the insurgents.{{sfn|Nolan|2011|p=248}}{{sfn|Comber|2015|p=100}} Crops grown by the insurgents were sprayed with [[herbicide]] and [[defoliant]]s with any of the involved areas that already found to be free from the insurgents will be elevated to \"white status\" with any previous restrictions were lifted.{{sfn|Ooi|2004|p=830}}{{sfn|Jackson|2008|p=49}}{{sfn|Hamblin|2013|p=175}}\n\n[[File:Anti-communist rally in Semenyih, Selangor during the ensuing Malayan Emergency, 1950s.jpg|thumb|left|A joint demonstration from ethnic Chinese and Malay in [[Semenyih]], Selangor who opposing the communist activities during the ensuing Malayan Emergency, {{circa|1950s}}.]]\nDespite large applause are given for his campaign, the root causes of the campaign success are mainly attributed to the continuous Briggs' Plan as expressed by the leader of the communist side [[Chin Peng]] where the massive resettlement of ethnic Chinese villagers resulted in the isolation of the communist movement.{{sfn|Gentile|2013|p=52}} Apart from that, the various early moves made by his predecessor Gurney for the introduction of a quasi-ministerial system with a bill to increase the number of non-Malays to be eligible for citizenship in the path towards independence also contributed to the victory.{{sfn|Tarling|1992|p=376}} Even with the hearts and minds issued by Templer throughout the war, there were also a massacre named the [[Batang Kali massacre]] perpetrated by British security forces against unarmed ethnic Chinese civilians in late 1948.{{sfn|Hale|2013|p=432}} Following the [[Chinese Communist Revolution|fall of Kuomintang and the establishment of communist control]] in China in 1949, foreign missionaries in the country were forced by the new communist authorities to leave which then invited by Templer to provide [[spiritual healing]] to the residents of the new government-controlled villages in Malaya where they also provide medical education and welfare measures to one-third of the Chinese population.{{sfn|Roy|Saha|2016|p=68}} By September 1952, Templer realised the citizenship plan with every people born in Malaya were granted full citizenship which include 1.2 million Chinese within the scheme.{{sfn|Roy|Saha|2016|p=67}}\n\n[[File:Photo of ancient Penang inside a room.jpg|thumb|right|The bustling town of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in Penang Island with many Chinese businesses and shoplots through [[industrialisation|industrial]] era since the British administration, {{circa|1950s}}.]]\nBy the time when the [[Federation of Malaya]] attained its independence from the British in 1957, there were still conflicts with the communists.{{sfn|Great Britain. Colonial Office|1957|p=469}} The ethnic Chinese communist members who surrendered were given the choice whether they want to be repatriated to China or return to their normal lives by showing their loyalty to the elected government of Malaya and giving up their communist ideology to which they will be helped by the government.{{sfn|Great Britain. Colonial Office|1957|p=4}} The campaign against communists by the newly independent country continued until 1960 when the Malayan government declared the end of [[state of emergency]] after Chin Peng decided to abandon its armed struggle with the demobilisation of its armed units thus leaving his hide-out in southern [[Thailand]] for [[Beijing]] through [[North Vietnam]] where he was accommodated by the Chinese authorities in the [[International Liaison Department of the Communist Party of China|International Liaison Bureau]] with medical benefits and monthly allowances.{{sfn|Singh|2014|p=39}}{{sfn|Garver|2015|p=200}} Through the meeting between the leader of Malayan communist with high-ranking Chinese communist politician such as [[Deng Xiaoping]] in Beijing, China urged them to continue their armed struggle, convincing the Communist Party of Malaya to reverse the policy they had decided earlier.{{sfn|Singh|2014|p=41}} The success of the establishment of a communist government in [[Mainland China]] also had great effect on the ethnic Chinese community in Sarawak, especially younger generations when they organised themselves into pro-Beijing friendship society of Sarawak Overseas Chinese Democratic Youth League and following local government vigilance that resulting to its disestablishment, it was re-established into Sarawak Advanced Youths' Association which later culminating into the [[communist insurgency in Sarawak]] in 1960.{{sfn|der Kroef|1964|p=50\u201360}} Even the conflicts with communist ensued, the economic situation of Malaya continued to prosper with strong financial position and defined by [[World Bank]] as among the most prosperous in Asia with large dependent on tin and rubber industries inherited since the British era which is largely dominated by ethnic Chinese and Indian workforce.{{sfn|Gomes|2007|p=46}}{{sfn|World Bank|2010}}\n\n=== Struggle for equality under the proposed Malaysian Malaysia (1963\u20131965) ===\n{{see also|Malaysian Malaysia}}\n[[File:Malaysian Solidarity Convention meeting in Singapore, 1965.jpg|thumb|left|[[Lee Kuan Yew]] together with other party leaders and representative from [[Malay Peninsula]] and [[Sarawak]] through the [[Malaysian Solidarity Convention]] meeting in Singapore, 1965.]]\nEarly in 1961 when Malayan Prime Minister [[Tunku Abdul Rahman]] outlined the idea for a \"Grand Malaysian Alliance\" comprising the British protectorate of [[Brunei]] and Crown colonies of North Borneo, [[Crown Colony of Sarawak|Sarawak]] and [[Colony of Singapore|Singapore]],{{sfn|Bunnell|2004|p=76}} the leader of Singapore under ethnic Chinese [[Lee Kuan Yew]] who is also against the communist movement become the utmost supporter towards the proposal with its party of [[People's Action Party]] (PAP) rallying for equality for all future Malaysians, regardless of their \"class, skin colour or creed\" with equal concept rested on a multi-ethnic society involving each of races in the entities which is not solely to be \"[[Malayisation|Malayised]]\" after the merger.{{sfn|Purushotam|2000|p=209}}{{sfn|Josey|2013|p=153}} Although Lee were seen by Malay extremes in the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) and [[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) as being anti towards [[Ketuanan Melayu|Malay special rights]] in the new federation following his criticism towards the unbalanced system between every races after the formation of Malaysia in 1963,{{sfn|Cheah|2002|p=54}}{{sfn|Akbarzadeh|Saeed|2003|p=142}} the Singaporean leader had earlier adopted [[Malay language]] as the national language of Singapore and appointed the first [[Yang di-Pertuan Negara]], [[Yusof Ishak]] from the Malay ethnicity.{{sfn|Tan|2004b|p=42}}\n\n[[File:Crowd attendance during the Malaysian Solidarity Convention, 1965.jpg|thumb|right|Crowd attendance during the Malaysian Solidarity Convention in Singapore, 1965.]]\nThe [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA) as the successor of Malayan Chinese Association and representative of ethnic Chinese in Malay Peninsula led by [[Tan Cheng Lock]] which has been part of the [[Alliance Party (Malaysia)|Malaysian Alliance Party]] refused to joined in the struggle for equality as they feared it will disrupted an earlier consensual agreement that has been agreed in Malaya between UMNO and the [[Malaysian Indian Congress]] (MIC), in which the Malays hold the country political dominance, the Chinese control the country economic sectors while [[Malaysian Indians|Indians]] playing a lesser economic role but within a gradual specific time frame the Malays will later partaking the sharing of economic with the Chinese and Indians partaking some aspects of political power.{{sfn|Ooi|2004|p=55}} After two years being part of a newer federation, especially following the controversial enactment of [[Article 153 of the Constitution of Malaysia|Article 153]] to the [[Constitution of Malaysia]], Lee is joined by two parties in the Malay Peninsula, the [[United Democratic Party (Malaysia)|United Democratic Party]] led by [[Lim Chong Eu]] and [[People's Progressive Party (Malaysia)|People's Progressive Party]] led by [[D. R. Seenivasagam]] as well two from Sarawak such as the [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party]] led by [[Ong Kee Hui]] and Machinda Party led by Michael Buma to form the [[Malaysian Solidarity Convention]] to continuously campaign for equality under Malaysian Malaysia.{{sfn|Cheah|2002|p=54}} During his speech at the Malaysian Solidarity Convention meeting in Singapore in June 1965, he expressed the political way based on race and religion currently practised in the Malay Peninsula:\n\n{{quote|It took a long time for us all to come to the same conclusions despite our differing experience in Malaya, Singapore, [[Sabah]] and [[Sarawak]]. Our friends in Sabah are not here today officially, but I can assure you that we have many friends there. There is no doubt about it that it took us a long time to reach inevitable conclusion that these people [referring to the racial politics in Malay Peninsula] were up to no good. You know the line they were taking with growing truculence on a heavy racial accent, the intimidatory postures and the snarling guttural notes on which they sent out their signals to their followers on the basis of race lead us to only one conclusion -- that if this goes on, Malaysia will not belong to [[Malaysians]]. Since there are so many Malaysians, we decided that the time has come for us to speak our minds.{{sfn|National Archives of Singapore|1965|p=1}}|Part of [[Lee Kuan Yew]] speech at the Malaysian Solidarity Convention in [[National Theatre, Singapore|National Theatre]], [[Singapore in Malaysia|Singapore]], June 1965.}}\n\nLee's further callings for the re-alignment of forces between those who wanted a \"true Malaysian nation\" or those who preferred a country led by communal segregation dominated by one of the constituent party from the Alliance together with his attacks on the Malay ultras for their attempts to foster only Malay dominance over the new country of Malaysia has led to a [[PAP\u2013UMNO relations|bitter relations between PAP and UMNO]] which further exaggerated into [[1964 race riots in Singapore|race riots in Singapore]] earlier in 1964 and leading to [[Singapore in Malaysia|their expulsion]] from the federation in August 1965.{{sfn|Cheah|2002|p=54}}{{sfn|Diamond|Plattner|Chu|2013|p=187}}{{sfn|Reid|2015|p=362}}\n\n=== Further conflicts and ethnic clashes (1965\u20131990) ===\nThe struggle for equality concept are then being continued by a new party established in the Malay Peninsula shortly after in 1965, the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) as PAP successor following the latter expulsion from the federation.{{sfn|Akbarzadeh|Saeed|2003|p=142}} Many ethnic Chinese in the Malay Peninsula soon began to perceive their ethnic party representative, the MCA are only concerned with business and economic interests than social factors since the party itself being led by wealthy Chinese with entire decision making fell under the influence of UMNO with persistent reminder by Prime Minister Tunku Abdul Rahman to the whole nation that MCA should be the sole legitimate representative for the ethnic Chinese community in the federation.{{sfn|Akbarzadeh|Saeed|2003|p=142}} By 1968, the communists with the support of Mainland China communist government began to gain ground by launching [[Communist insurgency in Malaysia (1968\u201389)|a new insurgency]] from their stronghold in southern Thailand in the heightened disagreement between the local ethnic Chinese and Malay in local political scene with the issuance of a directive entitled \"Hold High the Great Red Banner of Armed Struggle and Valiantly March Forward\" by the Central Command of the Communist Party of Malaya with guerrilla attacks on Malaysian security forces resulting to significant amount of success and considerable losses to the latter.{{sfn|Razak|2015|p=69}}{{sfn|Ong|2014|p=95}} The following year when the [[1969 Malaysian general election]] being held, MCA faced strong challenges from the new ethnic Chinese representative parties, the DAP together with [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Malaysian People's Movement Party]] (GERAKAN). Of the 33 parliamentary seats contested during the election, MCA only managed to retain 13 seats and lost its control over the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] to GERAKAN with subsequent gain by the opposition parties led to further tension between the Chinese and Malay which erupted into the [[13 May incident|13 May riots]].{{sfn|Charles|Cheng|1971|p=47}}{{sfn|der Kroef|1981|p=107}} The clashes since then largely affecting the ethnic sentiments between the two groups in Malay Peninsula including in neighbouring Singapore which have similarly enduring clashes early in 1964 when it still part of Malaysia.{{sfn|Kua|2007|p=74}}\n\nIn the aftermath of the riots that sent severe shock through the whole Malaysian society, Prime Minister Tunku Abdul Rahman placed the blame entirely on the communists rather than race issues plaguing both the ethnic Chinese and Malay, holding the view that Mainland China communist government was trying to do the similar things with what had been did by [[Soviet Union]] to eastern Europe, further in the opinion that the ongoing [[Vietnam War]] in their neighbour was \"not simply a civil war but [[domino theory|communist ideology expansion]]\".{{sfn|Cheng|2009|p=66}} Instead of declaring a state of emergency as done by the British authorities previously, the Malaysian government responded by introducing several policy initiatives including the security and development, neighbourhood watch program and the [[The People's Volunteer Corps|People's Volunteer Group]].{{sfn|Nazar|2005|p=19\u201320}} With the internal conflicts within the Communist Party of Malaya in the 1970s, the group split into two factions of [[Communist Party of Malaya/Revolutionary Faction|revolutionary]] in 1970 and [[Communist Party of Malaya/Marxist\u2013Leninist|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] in 1974.{{sfn|Chin|2003|p=467\u2013468}} The communists struggle suffered setbacks when both [[Kuala Lumpur]] and Beijing began to established [[China\u2013Malaysia relations|diplomatic relations]] in 1974 with China ending their aid to the movement, causing the merger between the two separated factions into the [[Malaysian Communist Party]] in 1983 before they surrendering to Thai authorities in 1987 following [[Communist insurgency in Thailand|continuous offensives]] by the latter with subsequent [[Peace Agreement of Hat Yai (1989)|peace agreement]] between Malaysian authorities and the communists movement in 1989.{{sfn|Khoo|2010}}{{sfn|Chin|2003|p=450}} Another communist insurgency by predominantly ethnic Chinese in Sarawak which partly supported by neighbouring Indonesia for their opposition towards the federation of Malaysia also ended through peace negotiations in 1990.{{sfn|Porritt|2004|p=279}}\n\n=== Present situation (1990\u2013present) ===\n[[File:Street in Happy Valley, George Town, Penang.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Variety of ethnic Chinese businesses from clinic, restaurant and grocery stores in Happy Valley of George Town in [[Penang]].]]\nAs a legacy of the [[divide and rule]] colonial policy imposed since the British administration, the division have lasting impact on the present-day ethnic relations in Malaysia which further exacerbated by agreement between race-based parties formed prior to the country formation.{{sfn|Tong|2010|p=95}} The failure to live under equal concepts has led to \"strong identification with [[Chinese identity]]\" from every ethnic Chinese Malaysians in contrast with what had long been practised by other Southeast Asian Chinese in neighbouring [[Chinese Indonesians|Indonesia]], [[Chinese Filipino|Philippines]], [[Chinese Singaporeans|Singapore]], [[Thai Chinese|Thailand]] and [[Hoa people|Vietnam]].{{sfn|Tong|2010|p=95}}{{sfn|Chen|2004|p=66}} In the aftermath of ethnic clashes in 1969 between the Chinese and Malay, the further implementation of [[Malaysian New Economic Policy]] favouring the Malays from 1971 until 1990 resulting the increase of [[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|Bumiputera]] economic control by 60%.{{sfn|Gomez|2012|p=1}} Nevertheless, since the country foundation even with previous agreement of their limitation in political matters and other controversial policy, ethnic Chinese Malaysian remain the traditional dominant player in the business sector of the [[Economy of Malaysia|Malaysian economy]] with [[equity (finance)|equity]] ownership doubled from only 22.8% in 1969 to 45.5% in 1990 and [[List of Malaysians by net worth|almost every of rich people in the country]] are dominated by the latter.<ref>{{harvnb|Ooi|2004|p=55}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Gomez|2012|p=2}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Jesudason|1997}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Malott|2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Petaling Street, Kuala Lumpur.jpg|thumb|right|[[Petaling Street]], a [[Chinatown]] in Malaysia's capital of [[Kuala Lumpur]], as seen at night]]\nSince ethnic Chinese Malaysians manage the country's economy, most of them reside in urban areas with statistics in 1991 found that about three-quarters (75.8%) mostly living in the country towns and cities.{{sfn|Kam|Tan|2000|p=78}} The continual disparity causing many modern ethnic Chinese Malaysian do not normally speak Malay among themselves,{{sfn|Wang|Wang|1998|p=31}} in contrast to the earlier ethnic Chinese who had mix with local Malay or other indigenous people such as the Straits-born Chinese of Baba-Nyonya, Kelantanese and Terengganuan [[Peranakan]]s, [[Penangite Chinese|Penangite Hokkien]] and Sabah Sino-Natives.{{sfn|Tan|2004|p=93\u201395}}{{sfn|Wong|2004|p=55}}{{sfn|Tong|2010|p=110}} Ethnic Chinese Malaysian in [[East Malaysia]] on both Sabah and Sarawak, especially in small inland towns also interact more closely with indigenous people there with the absence of significant language and religious barrier which further resulted in more interracial marriage among them.{{sfn|Tong|2010|p=110}} Major issues of integration in modern Malaysian nation as a whole today is largely inherited from the past Malayan racial politics especially when contacts between ethnics are only made between several sub-communities which eventually consolidated into a single political community.{{sfn|Enloe|1968|p=372\u2013385}} The discriminate affirmative policy and [[hierarchy]] continually practised in Malaysia's modern [[Education in Malaysia|education system]] and workplace in the 21th century further causing the [[human capital flight|brain drain]] trends among young educated and talented ethnic Chinese Malaysian to different [[developed countries]].{{sfn|Jakobsen|2014|p=170}}{{sfn|Tyson|2018|p=55}} Despite the rising brain drain among the youth, the country also saw the latest wave of newer ethnic Chinese [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]-speaking immigrants from northeastern China, and another from new small mixture with [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] since 2000s following the increasing small number of ethnic Chinese Malaysian, especially men marrying foreign wives from Mainland China and [[Vietnam]].{{sfn|Samantha|2016}} \n\n== Origins and social demographics ==\n{{see also|Chinese emigration|Overseas Chinese}}\n[[File:Origin of ethnic Chinese Malaysians.svg|thumb|left|Map of the geographic origin of the present-day ethnic Chinese Malaysians since their early migrations from China to [[Nanyang (region)|Nanyang]] region more than hundred years ago.{{sfn|Samantha|2016}}]]\nSince their early ancient trade connection and subsequent migrations, the majority of ethnic Chinese in Malaysia are mostly from [[Han Chinese|ethnic Han]] from the historical areas of [[Fujian]] and [[Guangdong]] provinces in [[southern China]].{{sfn|Simon|1996|p=51}} Nearly all ethnic Chinese Malaysians living in the country today are either [[patrilineality|patrilineal]] descendants of these early immigrants, or new immigrants born in mainland China.{{sfn|Tan|1997|p=103\u2013116}} Among the first group from the first migration wave are the Peranakans in [[Kelantan]] and [[Terengganu]], Sino-Natives in [[Sabah]] and Straits-born Chinese (Baba-Nyonya) in [[Malacca]] and [[Penang]].{{sfn|Tan|2004|p=93\u201395}}{{sfn|Wong|2004|p=55}}{{sfn|Oxford Business Group|2008|p=12}} The [[Taiping Rebellion]] in the mid-19th century caused much chaos and suffering in southern China, which leading many ethnic Chinese civilians to sought refuge overseas, particularly to [[Nanyang (region)|Nanyang]] region in further south.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=698}} With the expanding British colonial economies in the region which led to the establishment of [[Straits Settlements]], more migrants were attracted and primary become the important destination for [[Chinese emigration]].{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=698}}\n\n[[File:Southern Chinese (From Fukien), Merchant in Penang.JPG|thumb|right|An 1880 painting of southern Chinese merchant from [[Fujian]] (left) and Chinese official in [[Penang Island]].]]\nBy the late 19th century with the second wave of migration through the British colonial rule, the [[Hokkien people|Hokkien]] of southern Fujian led by many of their wealthy and powerful individuals with skills in [[finance]] and [[maritime shipping]] became the dominant immigrant group as the first group of ethnic Chinese to settle in large numbers with their language become a [[contact language]] among Chinese of different linguistics background.<ref>{{harvnb|Gosling|Lim|1983|p=89}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Menkhoff|1993|p=47}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Kuhn|2008|p=47}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Wurm|M\u00fchlh\u00e4usler|Tryon|2011|p=698}}</ref> The [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] from Canton in Guangdong follow suit and became well known as mineworkers, [[land reclamation]], mechanics and their familiarity with [[cash crop]]ping.{{sfn|Reid|Rodgers|2001|p=82}}{{sfn|Kuhn|2008|p=47}} Another large group, the [[Hakka people|Hakka]] are mostly hill farmers originated from northeastern Guangdong and various southern China places who specialise in forest clearance, mining as well on [[metalworking]].{{sfn|Reid|Rodgers|2001|p=82}}{{sfn|Kuhn|2008|p=47}} Other groups like the [[Teochew people|Teochew]] from [[Chaozhou]] of eastern Guangdong are mainly on [[plantation]] agriculture,{{sfn|Reid|Rodgers|2001|p=82}}{{sfn|Kuhn|2008|p=47}} the [[Foochow people|Foochow]] from central Fujian specialise in [[entrepreneurship]],{{sfn|Kaur|2016|p=194}} while the [[Hainanese people|Hainanese]] from [[Hainan]] as one of the ethnic Chinese minority saw themselves as [[:wikt:sojourner|sojourners]] with many of Hainanese chefs and waiters ruled the kitchen of local Chinese [[kopi tiam]] and [[restaurant]]s.{{sfn|Tan|2002|p=20}}{{sfn|Sharp|2008|p=1}} The [[Putian people|Henghua]] and Hokchia from eastern Fujian are usually managing family industries while the Kwongsai from [[Guangxi]] are employed in labour sectors.{{sfn|Malaysian Historical Society|1969|p=34}}{{sfn|Douw|Post|1996|p=148}} Followed by the third wave of ethnic Chinese migration thereafter, this resulted Malaysia as being one of the country outside China and [[Taiwan]] with [[East Asian cultural sphere|largest population of Chinese speakers]] in the world.{{sfn|Samantha|2016}}{{sfn|Asmah|2004|p=52}} Following the establishment of diplomatic relationship between Mainland China and Malaysia in 1974, a [[:wikt:joint communiqu\u00e9|joint communiqu\u00e9]] was made between the two nations, which stated:\n\n{{cquote|The [[Government of China|Chinese government]] considers anyone of [[Chinese people|Chinese origin]] who has taken up his own will or acquired [[Malaysian nationality law|Malaysian nationality]] as automatically forfeiting [[Nationality Law of China|Chinese nationality]]. As for residents who retain Chinese nationality of their own will, the Chinese government, acting in accordance with its consistent policy, will enjoin them to abide by the law of the [[Government of Malaysia]], respect the customs and habits of the people there, and live in unity with them, and their proper rights and interests will be protected by the Government of China and respected by the Government of Malaysia.{{sfn|Camilleri|1975|p=27}}}}\n\n=== Ethnic distributions ===\n{{See also|Demographics of Malaysia}}\n\n{{Historical populations\n| align       = left\n| width       = 10em\n| shading     = off\n| percentages = on\n| 1970 |3555879\n| 1980 |4554664\n| 1991 |4623900\n| 2000 |5691908\n| 2010 |6392636\n| footnote    = Note: Main census is released every ten years.\n| source      = [https://dosm.gov.my/ Malaysian Population Statistics]\n}}\n[[File:Geographical distributions of ethnic Chinese Malaysians.svg|thumb|right|Geographical distributions of ethnic Chinese Malaysians by majority in each cities or towns:<br />{{legend|#ABFFAB|[[Hokkien people|Hokkien]]}}{{legend|#E681FF|[[Cantonese people|Cantonese]]}}{{legend|#8181FF|[[Hakka people|Hakka]]}}{{legend|#FFE781|[[Foochow people|Foochow]]}}{{legend|#87CDDE|[[Hainanese people|Hainanese]]}}{{legend|#FFB380|[[Teochew people|Teochew]]}}{{legend|#8DD35F|[[Guangxi|Kwongsai]]}}{{legend|#DECD87|[[Fuqing dialect|Hockchia]]}}{{legend|#C5C9B8|Undetermined majority}}]]\n\nThe first census conducted in 1970 after Malaysia was formed in 1963 reported that there were 3,555,879 ethnic Chinese Malaysians, with the [[Hokkien people|Hokkien]] or Min Nan (\u798f\u5efa\u4eba or \u95fd\u5357\u4eba) being the majority at 32.4%, followed by [[Hakka people|Hakka]] (\u5ba2\u5bb6\u4eba) at 22.1%, [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] (\u5e7f\u5e9c\u4eba) at 19.8%, [[Teochew people|Teochew]] (\u6f6e\u6c55\u4eba) and [[Hainanese people|Hainanese]] (\u6d77\u5357\u4eba) at 12.4% and 4.7% respectively.{{sfn|Wang|2012|p=12}} This increase to 4,554,664 in 1980 and 4,623,900 in 1991.{{sfn|Yamaguchi|Deterding|2016|p=4}} In 2000, the census reported the ethnic Chinese Malaysians numbered at 5,691,908 (24.45%) from the total of 22,274,690 of the country population at the time with 86% of the ethnic Chinese living in urban areas.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=698}} In [[West Malaysia]], Hokkien became the leading group followed by Cantonese, Hakka and Teochew.{{sfn|Kam|Tan|2000|p=39}} The pattern differs in East Malaysia where Hakka is the majority in Sabah and Sarawak followed by Hokkien and Cantonese in Sabah and the [[Foochow people|Foochow]] (\u798f\u5dde\u4eba), Hokkien and Teochew in Sarawak.{{sfn|Kam|Tan|2000|p=47}}{{sfn|T'ien|1983|p=278}}{{sfn|Yong|2013|p=291}} In 2010, the population increase further to 6,392,636.{{sfn|Department of Statistics Malaysia|2010a|p=15}}\n\nThe Hokkien are notably prominent in the states of [[Johor]], [[Kedah]], Kelantan, Malacca, Penang, [[Perlis]], Sarawak, Labuan and Terengganu while the Hakka is prominent in Sabah and the second largest sub-group in [[Labuan]].{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=699}} The Cantonese are mostly concentrated in the cities of Kuala Lumpur and Ipoh, and to some extent in [[Bera District|Bera]], [[Kuantan]], [[Bentong District|Bentong]], [[Lipis District|Lipis]], [[Mersing]], [[Raub District|Raub]], [[Cameron Highlands]], [[Jerantut District|Jerantut]], [[Temerloh District|Temerloh]], [[Bahau]], [[Kampar, Perak|Kampar]], [[Rompin District|Rompin]], [[Gopeng]], [[Maran District|Maran]], [[Tapah]], [[Pekan District|Pekan]], [[Bidor]] and [[Seremban]] as well as [[Sandakan]] and [[Keningau]] ([[Taishanese people|Taishanese]] or \u53f0\u5c71\u4eba) in Sabah and [[Sarikei]] in Sarawak.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=699}} The Teochew are mostly in Johor and coastal Perak.\n\nThe Foochows are numerous in [[Yong Peng]], [[Sitiawan]], [[Sungai Pelek]], [[Bintangor, Sarawak|Bintangor]], [[Sarikei]] and [[Sibu]].{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=699}}{{sfn|Lee|Suryadinata|2012|p=114}} The population of Hainanese can be found in all cities and towns in Malaysia, numerously in Malacca and Terengganu together with the smaller population of Kwongsais or Guangxi (\u5e7f\u897f\u4eba) in [[Pahang]] and [[Putian people|Henghuas]] or Putian (\u5174\u5316\u4eba or \u8386\u7530\u4eba) and Hockchia or Fuqing (\u798f\u6e05\u4eba) in various other areas.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=699}} \n\nThere is also a small community of ''[[Hu\u00e1b\u011bi]]-ren'' (Northern Chinese or \u534e\u5317\u4eba) in Sabah whose ancestors coming from various parts of [[Hebei]] (\u6cb3\u5317) and [[Shandong]] (\u5c71\u4e1c) provinces in China with most of them calling themselves as ''[[Ti\u0101nj\u012bn]]-ren'' (\u5929\u6d25\u4eba or \u6d25\u4fa8). Besides that, Sanjiang-ren ({{zh|[[:zh:\u4e09\u6c5f\u4eba|\u4e09\u6c5f\u4eba]]}}) is a collective term used to categorise the group of people whose ancestors hailed from Shanghai (\u4e0a\u6d77), Zhejiang (\u6d59\u6c5f), Jiangsu (\u6c5f\u82cf), Hubei (\u6e56\u5317) and Jiangxi (\u6c5f\u897f). It is a sub group of mixed spoken dialects and has the least number of people as compared to other Chinese sub groups. The first San Jiang Clansmen Association or San Kiang Association was formed in Penang back in 1897.<ref name=\"History of Penang San Kiang Association\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.penangsankiang.org/archive.php?file=1|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=699}} \n\nAlthough the ethnic Chinese population had been increasing since the 1970s, their proportion within the total population had been decreasing gradually, particularly caused by the lower [[birth rate]] among the Chinese community.{{sfn|Wang|2012|p=12}}\n\n=== Economic and political representation ===\n{{see also|Economy of Malaysia|Bamboo network}}\nEthnic Chinese Malaysians have been traditionally dominant in the business sector of the Malaysian economy with large local Chinese enterprises involved in [[natural resources]] and food ingredients industries such as [[sugar]] and [[palm oil]].{{sfn|Voon|2007|p=234}} Almost every [[biscuit]]s manufacturers in the country also dominated by ethnic Chinese Malaysians.{{sfn|May|2015}} Up to the 1970s, their economic structure was interwined with very much family and [[kinship]] ties.{{sfn|Voon|2007|p=195}} By the 21st century with the [[Economy of China|rising of China's economic influence]], their [[business network|economy network]] are jointly connected with other [[Overseas Chinese]] through the [[bamboo network]].{{sfn|Weidenbaum|Hughes|1996|p=47}} The local Chinese played a key role in facilitating China's [[capital (economics)|capital]] to invest in Malaysia while in the process both benefited from expanded markets, lower labour costs and the introduction of different kind of technologies and managerial systems which resulted Malaysia becoming the largest trading partner to China in [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]] (ASEAN) region.{{sfn|Wong|Tan|2017|p=113}} Nevertheless, unlike the more trans-boundary business influence by neighbouring [[Chinese Singaporeans]], a majority of Chinese Malaysians businesses are still seen as less concentrating on developing business ties with other Southeast Asian Chinese businessmen despite there have been few business made by several local Malaysian Chinese companies.{{sfn|Gomez|2012|p=185}}\n\n[[File:Malaysia election results map by ethnicity, 2018.svg|thumb|320px|left|Proportion of ethnic Chinese and Malay with indigenous voters in the [[Results of the 2018 Malaysian general election by parliamentary constituency|2018 Malaysian parliamentary constituency]]:<br />{{legend|#FF0000|Bright red indicates a higher proportion of ethnic Chinese}}{{legend|#00F00F|Bright green indicates a higher proportion of [[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|ethnic Malay or indigenous people]]}}{{legend|#669A00|Mixed colour means that the ratio of the two is equivalent}}{{legend|#B65D24|The brownish colour are the area with the higher proportion of other non-indigenous races (such as [[Malaysian Indians|Indians]])}}]]\nSince the country's foundation in 1963, the [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA) had become the sole legitimate political representation for ethnic Chinese in Malaysia under the multi-racial political coalition of the [[Alliance Party (Malaysia)|Alliance Party]] (later expanded into [[Barisan Nasional|National Front]] coalition).{{sfn|Cartier|2011|p=71}} The growing restriction of non-Malay interests in Malaysian society and politics since the 1970s, however, caused a deep dissension among Chinese Malaysians. There grew a wide perception that their ethnic party representatives were unable to stand for their people's rights, and that decision-making was influenced by the Malay [[supremacism|supremacists]] dominated party of [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO). The UMNO were part of the existing political coalition, and also championed Islamic values.<ref>{{harvnb|Strauch|1981|p=37}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Weiner|\u00d6zbudun|1987|p=136}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Teck|1988|p=18}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|The Coverage|2019}}</ref> Despite the coalition's multi-racial appearance, UMNO founding president [[Onn Jaafar]] has once said that their movement did not adhere to any ideology other than \"[[Malayisation|Malayism]]\", defined by Malay scholar [[Ariffin Omar]] as the belief that the interests of the Malay race must be upheld over anything else.{{sfn|Ting|2009|p=35}} Until 1968, the inability of MCA to preserve ethnic Chinese Malaysian interests, particularly with regards to their culture, education and language, resulted in the formation of another ethnic Chinese representative party, the [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Malaysian People's Movement Party]] (GERAKAN) led by Chinese overseas-educated elite, although this party also joined the Alliance Party coalition in 1972.{{sfn|Jenkins|2008|p=91}}\n\nWith the growing [[Islamisation]] with \"Islamic version of non-tolerant and open\" as well increasing [[racism]] within the Malay party members throughout the coalition administration which further being imposed into the country social demographics causing further disenchantment among non-Malays especially ethnic Chinese together with the government discriminal policies on their education and employment.<ref>{{harvnb|Weiner|\u00d6zbudun|1987|p=136}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Bakri|2007|p=232}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Joseph|Nadirsyah|2010|p=94}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Lahoud|Johns|2012|p=177}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|The Coverage|2019}}</ref> This subsequently causing dwindle support from ethnic Chinese Malaysians when many Chinese [[List of Malaysian electoral districts|constituents]] which are originally the stronghold of MCA turned to the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) as the latter were seen as more vocal on their rights.{{sfn|Weiner|\u00d6zbudun|1987|p=136}}{{sfn|Coplin|1991|p=9}}{{sfn|Case|2013|p=105}} The [[2018 Malaysian general election|recent country general election in 2018]] saw the fall of National Front coalition following additional aid from Bornean parliamentary seats particularly in Sabah that were won by [[Pakatan Harapan]] coalition ally of [[regionalism (politics)|regionalist]] [[Sabah Heritage Party]] (WARISAN) as well from another indigenous party of [[United Pasokmomogun Kadazandusun Murut Organisation]] (UPKO) as a result of similar growing frustration over long-time manipulation of the state demographics and resources with lack of development through the administration of the Malay-led supremacists government of UMNO with frequent labelling as \"fixed deposit state\".{{sfn|Sipalan|Menon|2018}}{{sfn|The Borneo Post|2019}}{{sfn|Stephanie|2018}} During the election, the DAP won large amount of seats in many Chinese constituents and subsequently diminish MCA influence among ethnic Chinese Malaysians.{{sfn|Cheng|Faris|2018}}{{sfn|Dayley|2018|p=203}}{{sfn|Sukumaran|2019}}\n\n=== Contributions towards local medical practice ===\n{{see also|Traditional Chinese medicine}}\n[[File:Traditional Chinese Medicine Shop, George Town, Penang.jpg|thumb|280px|right|An ethnic Chinese woman in Malaysia grid and cut up dried [[Chinese herbology|herbs]] to make the [[traditional Chinese medicine]].]]\n\nAside from their economic dominance, ethnic Chinese Malaysians are known for their contribution in the country [[healthcare]] sectors with their traditional health practice. Around 3,000 medicine shops in the country sell traditional Chinese medicine with development support also given by the country [[Ministry of Health (Malaysia)|Health Ministry]].{{sfn|Stevenson|Tai|Yuan|2014|p=282}} Chinese traditional health practice services in the country generally encompass the ''zhong yi'' (Chinese medicine), ''[[qigong]]'' (health), [[chiropractic care]], [[acupuncture]] and several others.{{sfn|Beh|2017}} In 2012, the Traditional and Complementary Medicine Bill (T&CM) was passed by the [[Parliament of Malaysia]] for the establishment of \"Traditional and Complementary Medicine Council\" to register and regulate traditional and complementary medicine practitioners, including traditional Chinese medicine practitioners as well Malay, indigenous and Indians traditional medicine which followed by the enforcement of T&CM Act in the following year.{{sfn|Ministry of Health Malaysia|2015|p=10}} Since most of the traditional medicine pharmacies are family-apprentice trade, most of the traditional medicine practitioners are not registered as a doctor under the health department despite support given by the Health Ministry with most can practice the career without needed to be registered under government law.{{sfn|Stevenson|Tai|Yuan|2014|p=282}}\n\n=== Education ===\n{{see also|Chinese independent high school|Education in Malaysia}}\n[[File:Sabah Tshung Tsin Secondary School.JPG|thumb|left|Co-curricular activities in [[Sabah Tshung Tsin Secondary School|Tshung Tsin Secondary School]], a [[Chinese independent high school]] in [[Sabah]].]]\nIn educational aspects, Malaysia is the only country outside [[China]] and [[Taiwan]] with a comprehensive and complete Chinese education system and the only Southeast Asian country that has perpetuated the Chinese education system established since the colonial era as a result of heavy brokerage and lobbying efforts by ethnic Chinese Malaysians political leaders with continual funding from local Chinese communities.{{sfn|Curdt-Christiansen|Hancock|2014|p=145}}{{sfn|Ang|2017}} The first Chinese schools had been established in the country in the 19th century during the British colonial administration.{{sfn|Kam|Tan|2000|p=230}}{{sfn|Wong|2002b|p=35}}{{sfn|Charney|Yeoh|Tong|2003|p=147}} At the same time, Christian missions from China also founded schools for Chinese students to nurture Church workers, this are most notable among many Chinese Christians of Hakka origin in Sabah and the Foochow in Sarawak.<ref>{{harvnb|Ting|2011|p=38}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Charney|Yeoh|Tong|2003|p=147}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Bays|1996|p=165}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Goh|2005|p=52}}</ref> Following the country's independence, some of the Chinese independent schools who were influenced by the new national agenda and desperately needed government financial support were willingly converted into [[English-medium education|English medium-schools]]. However, these schools were later scrupulously converted into [[Malay language|Malay]] medium-schools following the massive elimination of English medium-schools by the Malay-dominated regime in the 1970s in an effort to impose the Malay language as the only medium of instructions in all schools in the aftermath of ethnic riots in 1969.{{sfn|Curdt-Christiansen|Hancock|2014|p=145}}{{sfn|Ang|2017}} The following period was considered a dark time for local Chinese education, and witnessed a growing belief in the idea that the ethnic Chinese in Malaysia had to proceed on a basis of self-reliance and vigilance in order to preserve their language rights as the national education policy was seen as exclusionary and discriminatory for non-Malays, summed up in the aphorism \"non-Malays belong to Malaysia but Malaysia only belongs to the Malays\".{{sfn|Curdt-Christiansen|Hancock|2014|p=145}}{{sfn|Kee|Hill|Yin|2016|p=75}}\n\n[[File:SMJK Confucian, 100-year anniversary.jpg|thumb|right|SMJK Confucian in Kuala Lumpur, an example of converted Chinese independent school to government-funded \"SMJK\" (literally ''[[:ms:Sekolah menengah jenis kebangsaan|Sekolah Menengah Jenis Kebangsaan]]'').]]\nAlthough other remaining Chinese independent schools were also included in the national school system in 1996, these independent schools still did not receive any financial assistance from the federal government and its United Examinations Certificate (UEC) is not recognised by the government, making students who finishing their studies from the local Chinese independent schools unable to enroll in government-funded public [[tertiary education|tertiary institutions]].{{sfn|Kee|Hill|Yin|2016|p=77}} Since the late 1970, ethnic Chinese Malaysians had expanded their own Mandarin-language primary schools where around 90% of their children were enrolled based on the figures from 2006.{{sfn|Nelson|Meerman|Rahman|2008|p=201}} These schools gained reputation for not only maintaining good discipline but also providing the high-quality education that the Malay schools were seen by some to lack. This perceived superiority attracted a significant interest among [[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|Bumiputera]] parents with various analyses placing the number of Bumiputera students enrollment in Chinese schools between 60,000\u2013100,000 in 2000.{{sfn|Nelson|Meerman|Rahman|2008|p=201}} The federal government's failure to impose Malay as the sole unifying language throughout the country's educational systems unlike in China with [[Standard Chinese]] or Indonesia with [[Indonesian language]] are mainly attributed to the racial-based policy enforcement of ethnic inclusion and exclusion.{{sfn|Kee|Hill|Yin|2016|p=78}} Some argue that the educational policies imposed by the federal government over the years in regard to minority language education have created negative consequences for Malaysian youth: a mounting [[human capital flight|brain drain]] in particular. A study from 2000 found that the country had lost an ample amount of talented and skilled youth to other more favourable countries as the result of students form the large non-Malay minority language communities being forced to go to university abroad because they did not attend Malay language schools.{{sfn|Defillippi|Arthur|Lindsay|2009|p=117}}{{sfn|Fong|Zubair|2017|p=15}}\n\n== Culture ==\n{{See also|Culture of Malaysia|East Asian cultural sphere}}\n\n[[File:Inside the Baba and Nyonya Heritage Museum.jpg|thumb|right|Inside the former house of a Peranakan (Baba-Nyonya or \u5cc7\u5cc7\u5a18\u60f9) in [[Malacca]] which has now been [[Baba Nyonya Heritage Museum|converted into a museum]], a nyonya can be seen sitting inside wearing the traditional ''[[kebaya#Kebaya Encim or Peranakan|kebaya]]''.]]\n\n[[Chinese culture|Chinese cultural influences]] made their mark when [[Silk Road|ancient trade relations]] were established with the [[Nanyang (region)|Nanyang]] (\u5357\u6d0b) region.{{sfn|Barbie J.|1992}} The massive ethnic Chinese migration during the British colonial period causing a subsequent strong influence on the country culture, including in cuisine and the language.{{sfn|Nazri|Shahrim|Farah|Mursyid|2017}} Aside from the Chinese cultural influence on local culture, ethnic Chinese from the first wave migration before English arrival had mainly adopted a localised culture.{{sfn|Kee|Choong|2006|p=83}} The Baba-Nyonya in Malacca had a very strong Malay influence in their clothing and food although still maintaining their Chinese heritage of religion, name and identity.{{sfn|The Star|2008}} Their food are made with Malay ingredients and recipes but produced using Chinese method while their houses are constructed with the infusion of [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]], [[Chinese architecture|Chinese]] and [[Malay architecture|Malay]] elements.{{sfn|The Star|2008}} Together with the Peranakans in Penang, both sides use a mixture of [[Hokkien]] and Malay despite the Penang Peranakans speak mainly Hokkien with some borrowed words from Malay words while in Malacca, the Peranakans have adopted Malay [[patois]] with some Hokkien words.{{sfn|Government of Penang}} The food prepared by Penang Peranakans also infuses both Chinese and Malay elements, albeit with an additional [[Thai cuisine|Thai influence]].{{sfn|Government of Penang}} The Peranakans in east coast of Malaysia in Kelantan and Terengganu have a much closer ties with the Malay and [[Malaysian Siamese|Siamese]] community there since most of them has adopted the Malay and Siamese lifestyle.{{sfn|Winzeler|1974|p=45\u201361}}{{sfn|Nazri|Hanapi|Teo|2011|p=112}}{{sfn|Carolyn|2015}}\n\n[[File:NaTukKong003.jpg|thumb|left|[[Na Tuk Kong]] (\u62ff\u7763\u516c) shrine in West Malaysia.]]\n\nA further close blood relations between ethnic Chinese and local indigenous in northern [[Borneo]] since the early kingdoms period produced the \"Sino-Natives\" persons in Sabah as a result of [[interracial marriage|inter-marriage]] between ethnic Chinese there and natives of Sabah.{{sfn|Zhang|2018|p=141}} Instead of speaking Chinese languages, these community spoke the localised [[Sabah Malay]] dialect as their main ''[[lingua franca]]'' since the 14th century.{{sfn|Zhang|2018|p=141}} The close relations is mark with earliest records of \"Kina\" term which is widely used by the indigenous [[Dusun people|Dusun]] to refer the Chinese ethnicity including for the Dusun homeland mountain of \"[[Mount Kinabalu]]\" (Chinese widow mountain), \"[[Kinabatangan River]]\" (Chinese river) and several other places such as the Kinabalu mountain stream of \"Kinataki\", a small river in northeastern coast of \"Kinaba\u00f1gun\" and a Chinese land in [[Labuan|Labuan Island]], the \"Kinabenua\".{{sfn|St. John|1863|p=327}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1893|p=155}} The [[Na Tuk Kong]] shrine for example shown another sign of assimilation with local culture, where it refers to local Malay guardian [[spirit]]s worshipped by some ethnic Chinese in West Malaysia and neighbouring [[Singapore]] and Indonesia.{{sfn|Lin|2017|p=126}} The term ''Na Tuk'' originated from the Malay word of ''[[Datuk]]'' (grandfather) which then merged with ''Kong'' (\u516c, sometimes addressed as 'Kung' meaning elderly male), similar with [[tudigong|Tu Ti Kung]] ({{zh|[[:zh:\u571f\u5730\u516c|\u571f\u5730\u516c]]}}), an earth deity worshipped in [[East Asia]].{{sfn|Hock|1996|p=8}}{{sfn|Lin|2017|p=125\u2013126}}\n\n=== Cuisine ===\n{{main|Malaysian Chinese cuisine}}\n[[File:Cuisine of Chinese Malaysian.jpg|thumb|right|Some of the examples of ethnic Chinese influenced Malaysian cuisine, clockwise from top-right: [[grass jelly]] (\u51c9\u7c89) with ''[[Bandung (drink)|Bandung]]'', ''[[yong tau foo]]'', ''[[kuih|Nyonya steamed layer cake]]'' (\u5a18\u60f9\u5343\u5c42\u7cd5) and [[laksa|''laksa'' noodle]].]]\nThe ethnic Chinese cuisine in Malaysia is derived from the culinary traditions of their early immigrants and descendants, who have adapted or modified their culinary traditions under the influence of Malaysian culture as well as immigration patterns of Chinese to the country where [[Chinese cuisine]] has now become an inseparable part from the country cultural mixture.{{sfn|Hutton|2012|p=24}} When Chinese merchants sailed their [[junk (ship)|junks]] across the [[South China Sea]], they visiting ports in Borneo and Malacca which then have profound influence in the region.{{sfn|Hutton|2012|p=24}} Chinese traders who visited Borneo always brought some good cooks with them since the local king in the island are very much liked Chinese food.{{sfn|Yuan|2000|p=19}} They introduced ingredients in Chinese cooking such as [[noodles]], [[bean sprouts]], [[tofu]] and [[soy sauce]] which is now widely used by every ethnic groups in the country.{{sfn|Hutton|2005|p=13}} Apart from introducing, these earlier traders also discovering worth ingredients among the local population along the coast, such as the expensive [[edible bird's nest]] with the best nests are claimed to come from Borneo than in China.{{sfn|Chen|1976|p=42}}{{sfn|Dunlop|1994|p=251}} Since a vast majority of Chinese Malaysians today are descendants of immigrants from [[South China|southern China]], local Chinese cuisine roots is predominantly based from [[Fujian cuisine|Fujian]], [[Cantonese cuisine|Cantonese]], [[Hakka cuisine|Hakka]] and [[Teochew cuisine|Teochew]] cuisines. Their technique of [[stir frying]] a portion of food ingredients in a little [[cooking oil]] over high heat in a [[wok]] (\u9505) are widely adopted.{{sfn|Hutton|2005|p=13}}\n\n[[File:Nyonya kuih kitchen.jpg|thumb|left|The Nyonya making various traditional ''[[kuih]]''.]]\n\nChinese Malaysians cuisine developed a strong penchant of [[spices]] and [[chillies]] where any local Chinese [[kopi tiam]] or restaurant will offer pickled green or red chillies ''[[sambal]]'' for noodles and rice-based meals.{{sfn|Hutton|2005|p=13}} They borrowed [[curry tree|curry leaves]] from the Indians and have since adapted English [[Worcestershire sauce]] and [[tomato sauce]] along with Indian and Malay spices to the [[cooking pot]].{{sfn|Hutton|2005|p=13}} Among the notable Chinese dishes in the country including the ''[[bak kut teh]]'' (\u8089\u9aa8\u8336) (pork rib soup with Chinese herbs), ''[[char kway teow]]'' (\u7092\u7cbf\u6761) (stir fried rice noodle), ''[[dim sum]]'' (\u70b9\u5fc3) (ready-to-serve dishes), ''[[hae mee]]'' (\u867e\u9762) (spicy prawn noodle soup served in savoury broth), [[Hainanese chicken rice]] (\u6d77\u5357\u9e21\u996d), ''kai si hor fun'' (\u9e21\u4e1d\u6cb3\u7c89) (flat rice noodle soup with chicken slices, shrimps and bean sprouts), ''[[kolo mee|kolok or kolo mee]]'' (\u5e72\u635e\u9762) (Sarawakian egg noodle served in dark sauce, tomato sauce or chilli sauce), ''[[lor mee]]'' (\u5364\u9762) (thick yellow noodle served in dark sauce and thick broth), ''ngiu chap mee'' (\u725b\u6742\u9762) (special Sabah mixed beef noodle), ''[[pan mee]]'' (\u677f\u9762) (handmade noodle soup served with pork balls, minced pork, dried anchovies, black fungus and vegetable), ''sang nyuk mee'' (\u751f\u8089\u9762) (special Sabah dry pork noodle or pork noodle soup), ''[[wonton noodle|wonton mee]]'' (\u4e91\u541e\u9762) (dry noodle or noodle soup served with BBQ pork, minced pork and pork or shrimp dumplings) and ''[[yong tau foo]]'' (\u917f\u8c46\u8150) (tofu and mixed vegetables filled with ground pork mixture or fish paste). Many Chinese Malaysians also can cook Malay-style chicken or fish with most versions of ''[[laksa]]'' (\u53fb\u5526) are prepared by them.{{sfn|Hutton|2005|p=13}} Some examples of basic Chinese Malaysians drinks commercially produced in the country including the [[black tea]], [[chrysanthemum tea]], [[grass jelly]], [[green tea]], [[jasmine tea]], [[soy milk]] and [[Ipoh white coffee|white coffee]] while popular snacks including the ''[[youtiao|cakoi]]'' (\u6cb9\u70b8\u9b3c) (long deep-fried dough), [[egg tart]], ''hum ji peng'' (\u54b8\u714e\u997c) (circle shaped fried dough with or without fillings), ''ngoi sing tart'' (\u5916\u661f\u5854) (UFO shaped tart), ''[[ngo hiang]]'' (\u70b8\u4e94\u9999) (various spiced, minced meat rolls prepared in deep fried style and served with vegetables), ''[[baozi|pau]]'' (\u5305) (steamed buns), ''[[popiah]]'' (\u8584\u997c) (fried or plain spring rolls filled with mixed vegetables), and ''tau sar piah'' (\u8c46\u6c99\u997c) (pastry biscuits filled with a sweet or savoury filling).{{sfn|Tan|2012|p=137}} The legacy from the first wave migration created the [[Peranakan]] (\u571f\u751f\u534e\u4eba) (including the Baba-Nyonya (\u5cc7\u5cc7\u5a18\u60f9)) ethnicity through a blend between Chinese and Malay which subsequently produced the [[Peranakan cuisine]] where they served Indian-style curries with eating [[etiquette]] different than mainstream ethnic Chinese society by following the Malay usage of fingers than [[chopsticks]].{{sfn|West|2010|p=486}} The Baba-Nyonya also specialised in making variety of local snacks called ''[[kuih]]'' which require plenty of patience and skills.{{sfn|Arokiasamy|2017|p=451}}\n\n=== Dialects and languages ===\n{{see also|Sinophone}}\n[[File:Map-Sinophone World.png|thumb|left|Map of [[Sinophone]] world where [[Chinese language]]s are spoken as a [[first language]] among ethnic Chinese in countries where their population is significant:<br />{{legend|#00AA00|Large Chinese speaking-majority (Coastal and central area of [[China]], including [[Taiwan]] and [[Singapore]])}}{{legend|#81C631|Large Chinese speaking-minorities (Highland China, including [[Malaysia]] and [[Brunei]])}}{{legend|#B2F273|Small Chinese-speaking minority ([[Vietnam]], [[Kyrgyzstan]] and the [[Philippines]])}}]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"1\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin: 0 0 1em 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; text-align:right; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 85%;\"\n|+ '''Example of Chinese loanwords in [[List of loanwords in Malay|Malay language]]'''\n|-\n! align=\"center\" style=\"background-color: #E9E9E9\" | Loanword\n! align=\"center\" style=\"background-color: #E9E9E9\" | English description\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|bihun/mihun}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[rice vermicelli]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|cakoi}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[youtiao|a long deep-fried dough]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|cawan}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[cup]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|cincai}}''\n| align=\"right\" | carelessly, in a hurry, random\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|cincau}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[grass jelly]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|ginseng}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[ginseng|root of herbal plants]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|kapcai}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[underbone|underbone motorcycle]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|kuaci}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[sunflower seed]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|kuetiau}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[char kway teow|rice noodle]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|kuih}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[kuih|snack and dessert]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|longkang}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[drainage]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|mee/mi}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[noodle]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|pau}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[baozi|steamed bun]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|popia/popiah}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[popiah|fried spring roll]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|samseng}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[gangster]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|tauhu}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[tofu]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|tauke}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[:wikt:towkay|big boss]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|teh}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[tea]]\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | ''{{lang|ms|tongkang}}''\n| align=\"right\" | [[junk (ship)|ancient Chinese sailing ship]]\n|- style=\"background: #E9E9E9;\"\n| colspan=\"2\" | Source: {{harvnb|Asmah|1975|p=40}} and [[Dewan Bahasa dan Pustaka|DBP]]\n|}\nThe 1970 Malaysian Census reported the [[Southern Min]] dialects being the largest which accounting for 34.2% of the country Chinese population, followed by [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]] with 22.1%, [[Cantonese]] by 19.8%, [[Chaozhou Chinese|Chaozhou]] (Teochew) by 12.4% and [[Hainanese]] by 4.7%.{{sfn|Wang|2012|p=12}} In 2003, a more detailed statistics for each dialects reported the [[Hokkien]] with 2,020,914, Hakka with 1,092,835, Cantonese with 1,068,008, Teochew with 497,280, [[Fuzhou dialect|Foochow]] with 251,553, Hainanese with 141,045, Kwongsai with 51,674, [[Pu-Xian Min|Henghua]] with 24,654, Hockchia with 14,935 and different other ethnic Chinese with 202,977, for a total of 5,365,875.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=698}} The Malaysian Hokkien are divided into two localised dialects; the [[Penang Hokkien]] (northern) comprising Kedah, Penang, Perak and Perlis and [[Southern Peninsular Malaysian Hokkien|Southern Peninsular Hokkien]] in Johor, Malacca and neighbouring Singapore.{{sfn|Armstrong|Armstrong|Mulliner|2012|p=218}} The northern Hokkien contains more Malay loanwords than the southern with the latter maintaining more of their original Hokkien words.{{sfn|Armstrong|Armstrong|Mulliner|2012|p=218}} Many Hokkien living in Sarawak have been influenced heavily by indigenous language similarly with Hokkien in Kelantan where their language were heavily localised following close interaction with local Malays and [[Malaysian Siamese|Siamese]].{{sfn|Armstrong|Armstrong|Mulliner|2012|p=218}} Localised Hokkien also spoken primarily by the Peranakan community (Baba-Nyonya) in both Malacca and Penang.{{sfn|Cheung|Tan|2007|p=171}} Generally, Hokkien became a contact language among ethnic Chinese of different linguistic background in most parts of Malaysia.{{sfn|Wurm|M\u00fchlh\u00e4usler|Tryon|2011|p=698}}\n\nThe [[Malaysian Cantonese]] became the contact language in the Malaysia's capital of Kuala Lumpur albeit with a distinct [[phonology]] and grammar from standard Cantonese spoken in [[Pearl River Delta]] region of China including in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]].{{sfn|Wurm|M\u00fchlh\u00e4usler|Tryon|2011|p=698}}{{sfn|Asmah|2004|p=51}}{{sfn|Bauer|Benedict|2011|p=281}} Hakka dialect assumes the role of contact language in Sabah but in the rest of the country the language are more commonly used as an intra-group language than a [[lingua franca]] within the Chinese community with about 66.2% of Hakka in Johor prefer [[Malaysian Mandarin|localised Mandarin]].{{sfn|Wang|2012|p=80}}{{sfn|Platt|Weber|Ho|1983|p=50}} Similar studies on [[Eastern Min]] speakers of Foochow community in Sarawak also found a general shift of language choice from their own dialect to [[Mandarin Chinese]] and [[English language|English]].{{sfn|Ball|2009|p=240}} The Chaozhou dialect despite being not a largest dialect group has become a bridge language for trade between Teochew exporters in China and wholesalers in Malaysia.{{sfn|Ma|Cartier|2003|p=85}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2011|p=124}} Hainan dialect is another minority and the sub-dialect of the [[Min Chinese]] dialect family although it is treated in the country as an independent dialect.{{sfn|Wang|2012|p=18}} Several others like Henghua are also generally termed as \"dialects\", which in fact together with the rest are [[Varieties of Chinese|variety of Chinese languages]] from different Chinese ethnicity.{{sfn|Asmah|1992|p=26}} Mandarin, which is generally spoken by northern Chinese minority in Sabah become the main [[working language]] among all Chinese in the country with [[Standard Mandarin]] is used as the [[medium of instruction]] in local Chinese medium school and [[Chinese independent high school|independent high school]] although the language still not necessarily spoken in their daily life practice.<ref>{{harvnb|Kam|Tan|2000|p=56}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Maya|2006|p=73}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Wurm|M\u00fchlh\u00e4usler|Tryon|2011|p=698}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Wang|2012|pp=16\u201317}}<br />{{*}} {{harvnb|Suryadinata|1989|p=166}}</ref> Based on early Malaysian Census in 1970, around 41% of ethnic Chinese Malaysians able to converse in Mandarin.{{sfn|Wang|2012|p=16\u201317}}\n\n=== Holidays and festivities ===\n{{see also|Public holidays in Malaysia}}\n[[File:Lion dance in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.jpg|thumb|left|[[Lion dance]] in Malaysia's capital during the Chinese main festivity.]]\nWith the large presence of ethnic Chinese in the country nationwide, the ethnic main festivity of [[Chinese New Year]] have been gazetted as a national public holiday with [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|11 states and three federal territories]] in the country celebrate the festive with two days holidays while two remaining states of Kelantan and Terengganu only celebrate a one-day holiday.{{sfn|Government of Malaysia|2019}} During the New Year, many Chinese living with their family in the urban areas will celebrate the festive together while some who may have family in rural areas will return for family reunions. A traditional dinner with entire family are the most important aspect on the celebration where there will also be a traditional food tossing culture of ''[[yusheng|yee sang]]'' especially among the Cantonese.{{sfn|Leong|1992|p=2}}{{sfn|DK Travel|2016|p=34}} The elder one will usually give the young a [[red envelope]] (''[[:wikt:ang pow|ang pow]]'' or ''angpau'') with [[Chinese candy box|variety of festival sweets]] are presented in the house for visitors. Most Chinese settlements and [[Chinatown]] streets will be decorated early before the New Year with colourful lanterns and lamps that will be shined at night throughout the festive. The performances of [[dragon dance|dragon]] and [[lion dance|lion]] dances will be presented throughout every Chinese settlements in the country with [[firecracker]] and [[fireworks]] shows also featured at night as part of the celebrations.{{sfn|DK Travel|2016|p=34}}\n\n[[File:Chinese New Year foods in Malaysia.jpg|thumb|right|Aside from [[mandarin orange]], various other snacks are presented for visitors throughout the Chinese New Year.]]\n\n[[Chingay parade|Chingay]] procession are also being held as part of the New Year festivities especially in Johor Bahru and Penang.{{sfn|Fodor|Fisher|1986|p=297}} Several other festivals are celebrated through the [[season]]s in a year including the [[Dongzhi Festival]], [[Dragon Boat Festival]], [[Hungry Ghost Festival]], [[Lantern Festival]] (''Chap Goh Mei''), [[Mid-Autumn Festival]], [[Nine Emperor Gods Festival]] and [[Qingming Festival]] which originated from much of [[Chinese folklore|Chinese folk beliefs]] and traditional agricultural society.{{sfn|Jaime|Stephanie|2009|p=132}} Throughout the festivals, especially for major Chinese festivals such as the New Year, Hungry Ghost and Mid-Autumn, nearly every Chinese temples including charity temples in the country will organise cultural and religious activities.{{sfn|Tan|2018|p=103}} The Hungry Ghost Festival is generally not observed by most ''[[De teaching|Dejiao]]'' (''Zi'') group in Malaysia which descended directly from ''Dejiao'' association in China, it is only mainly observed by three ''Zi'' associations in Kuala Lumpur (''Zi Fang Ge''), [[Pulau Ketam]] (''Zi Bang Ge'') and [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]] (''Zi Wei Gi'') with the three calling the festival as ''Wanyuan Shenghui'' than ''Yulan Shanghui''.{{sfn|Tan|1985|p=72}} The Mooncake Festival are popularly celebrated through the Mid-Autumn Festival where there will be the exchange and consume of [[mooncake]] as well lantern festival.{{sfn|DK Travel|2016|p=59\u201360}} Traditional [[Chinese marriage|Chinese weddings]] remain popular to some ethnic Chinese Malaysians couple even most have preferred the Western-influenced wearing of white [[wedding dress]]es and black [[black tie|jackets]].{{sfn|Ruby|2014}}\n\n=== Religion ===\n{{See also|Religion in Malaysia|Malaysian folk religion|Superstitions of Malaysian Chinese|Shenism in Southeast Asia}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| perrow   = 2\n| footer   = [[Chinese folk religion]], [[Confucianism]], [[Mah\u0101y\u0101na Buddhism]] and [[Taoism]] temples in Malaysia.\n| align    = left\n| width    = 150\n| image1   = MY-penang-george-kek-lok-si-tempel-garten-1.jpg\n| alt1     = Kek Lok Si\n| link1    = Kek Lok Si\n| image2   = Tian Wang Dian.jpg\n| alt2     = Jade Dragon Temple\n| link2    = Jade Dragon Temple\n| image3   = Sandakan Sabah Tam-Kong-Temple-01.jpg\n| alt3     = Tam Kung Temple\n| link3    = Tam Kung Temple, Malaysia\n| image4   = Sam Poh Tong Temple.jpg\n| alt4     = Sam Poh Tong Temple\n| link4    = Sam Poh Tong Temple\n}}\n{{Pie chart\n| caption = Religion of ethnic Chinese Malaysians (2010){{sfn|Department of Statistics Malaysia|2010b|p=15}}\n| label1  = [[Buddhism]]\n| value1  = 83.6\n| color1  = #FFDEAD\n| label2  = [[Christianity]]\n| value2  = 11.0\n| color2  = #7EC2EB\n| label3  = [[Chinese folk religion]]\n| value3  = 3.4\n| color3  = #E0FFFF\n| label4  = [[Irreligion|No religion]]\n| value4  = 0.8\n| color4  = #FF69B4\n| label5  = [[Islam]]\n| value5  = 0.7\n| color5  = #82D587\n| label6  = [[Hinduism]]\n| value6  = 0.2\n| color6  = #E8EB7E\n| label7  = Unknown\n| value7  = 0.17\n| color7  = #BDB7B3\n| label8  = Other religion\n| value8  = 0.13\n| color8  = #F0FFF0\n}}\n\nBased on the 2000 Malaysian Census, 86.6% of ethnic Chinese Malaysians follow [[Buddhism]] of [[Mah\u0101y\u0101na]] branch and [[Chinese folk religion]] with [[Chinese temple]]s and shrines are visible nationwide.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}} A more detailed statistics in 2010 found a total of 5,341,687 ethnic Chinese Malaysians of Buddhists adherents, 706,479 are [[Christianity|Christians]], 218,261 practising [[Confucianism]], [[Taoism]] and other [[Chinese folk religion]], 49,320 were [[irreligion|irreligious]], 42,048 are [[Islam|Muslims]], 14,878 are [[Hinduism|Hindus]], 11,387 with unknown religion while 8,576 practising other different religion.{{sfn|Department of Statistics Malaysia|2010b|p=15}} Among the common [[deities]] worshipped by ethnic Chinese Malaysians in temples are [[Guan Yu|Lord Guan]] (''Guangong Shengjun''), [[Guanyin|Guan Yin]] (''Goddess of Mercy''), [[Tua Pek Kong|Dabo Gong]] (''Earth God'') and [[Mazu]] (''Goddess of Heaven'').{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}}\n\nCommonly found in ethnic Chinese homes and shops are [[altar]]s installed for deities of their choice together with ancestors worship. Most of the deities are Chinese origin but it is still uncommon to sight a few of local deities.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}} There are different types of Chinese Buddhist temples and societies in every Malaysian cities and towns with only Buddhist statues, although some may have one or two other Chinese deities.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}} Other [[Schools of Buddhism|Buddhist branches]] of [[Therav\u0101da]] and various [[Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan]] traditions ([[Vajray\u0101na]]) also have Chinese members where it is not surprising that some of the other Buddhist branches buildings are build with the fund and [[philanthropic]] efforts of local Chinese Buddhists as exampled from the establishment of [[Buddhist Maha Vihara, Brickfields|Buddhist Maha Vihara]] in Kuala Lumpur and [[Wat Chayamangkalaram]] in Penang.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}}{{sfn|Khoo|2012|p=313}}{{sfn|Tan|2018|p=35}} Unlike the [[institutional religion]] of Buddhism, Christian and Islam, ethnic Chinese who follow traditional folk religion do not have separate name for their belief and practices which is similar to the country indigenous people such as [[Iban people|Iban]] and the [[Orang Asli]].{{sfn|Tan|2018|p=8}} They describe their religious belief as either ''bai shen'' or ''bai fo'' (deities worshipping) which include the worshipping of Buddha since the main Buddha deities are also commonly worshipped by the followers of Chinese traditional religion.{{sfn|Tan|2018|p=8}}\n\n[[File:Palm Sunday at St Ignatius Church in Petaling Jaya, Selangor.jpg|thumb|left|Chinese Christians during [[Palm Sunday]] at St Ignatius Church in [[Selangor]].]]\n\nChinese Christians, including both [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] and [[Protestants]] presence is mainly visible with their active missionary activities especially among ethnic Chinese in East Malaysia with large proportion than other regions.{{sfn|West|2010|p=485\u2013486}} The majority of Christians in West Malaysia also are of Chinese origin.{{sfn|Goh|2005|p=55}} Most early Chinese churches including [[Baptists]], [[Methodists]] and [[Presbyterians]] have their origin from missionaries migrants who introduced the missions established in China to Malaysia.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}} The number of Chinese Muslims are very small compared to Chinese Christians since the latter religion are seen as more tolerance and accepting, mainly due to the general perception that embracing [[Islam in Malaysia]] is like to become [[Malayisation|Malayised]] in addition to the ethnic rivalry between Malay and Chinese that makes Islam as less desirable to ethnic Chinese Malaysians.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}} A majority of Chinese Malaysians, especially those who have received Chinese education, following Confucian values and to a lesser extent with Taoism while their ordinary people who are less educated expressing in their view of [[filial piety]] and [[social relation]]s, consulting [[Chinese horoscope]]s as well on Chinese [[geomancy]] of ''[[feng shui]]''.{{sfn|Ember|Ember|Skoggard|2004|p=703}} Taoist activities gain increasing interests and significance among Chinese Malaysians although it is not deeply practised.{{sfn|Pas|1998|p=36}}{{sfn|Khoo|2014|p=2}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Malaysia|Taiwan|Society}}\n* [[List of Malaysians of Chinese descent]]\n* [[China\u2013Malaysia relations]]\n** [[Hong Kong\u2013Malaysia relations]]\n* [[Malaysia\u2013Taiwan relations]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|24em}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Academic publications and journal ===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite journal\n  | last = Purcell\n  | first = Victor\n  | year = 1947\n  | title = Chinese Settlement in Malacca\n  | journal = Journal of the Malayan Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society\n  | volume = 20\n  | pages = 115\u2013125\n | number = 1\n  | jstor = 41560007\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite journal\n  | last = Comber\n  | first = Leon\n  | year = 1956\n  | title = Chinese Secret Societies in Malaya; an Introduction\n  | journal = Journal of the Malayan Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society\n  | volume = 29\n  | pages = 146\u2013162\n | number = 1\n  | jstor = 41503202\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite journal\n  | last = Png\n  | first = Poh Seng\n  | year = 1961\n  | title = The Kuomintang in Malaya, 1912-1941\n  | journal = Journal of Southeast Asian History\n  | volume = 2\n  | pages = 1\u201332\n | number = 1\