\n  | title = Economic Change in East Malaysia: Sabah and Sarawak since 1850\n  | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan UK\n  | isbn = 978-0-230-37709-7\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Brezina\n  | first = Corona\n  | year = 2016\n  | title = Zheng He: China's Greatest Explorer, Mariner, and Navigator\n  | publisher = The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc\n  | isbn = 978-1-5081-7149-2\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | author = DK Travel\n  | year = 2016\n  | title = DK Eyewitness Travel Guide Malaysia and Singapore\n  | publisher = Dorling Kindersley Limited\n  | isbn = 978-0-241-25431-8\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Landa\n  | first = Janet Tai\n  | authorlink = Janet Tai Landa\n  | year = 2016\n  | title = Economic Success of Chinese Merchants in Southeast Asia: Identity, Ethnic Cooperation and Conflict\n  | publisher = Springer\n  | isbn = 978-3-642-54019-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Roy\n  | first1 = Kaushik\n  | last2 = Saha\n  | first2 = Sourish\n  | year = 2016\n  | title = Armed Forces and Insurgents in Modern Asia\n  | publisher = Routledge\n  | isbn = 978-1-317-23193-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Yamaguchi\n  | first1 = Toshiko\n  | last2 = Deterding\n  | first2 = David\n  | year = 2016\n  | title = English in Malaysia: Current Use and Status\n  | publisher = BRILL\n  | isbn = 978-90-04-31430-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Wong\n  | first1 = Bernard\n  | last2 = Tan\n  | first2 = Chee Beng\n  | year = 2017\n  | title = China's Rise and the Chinese Overseas\n  | publisher = Taylor & Francis\n  | isbn = 978-1-351-86660-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Lin\n  | first = Francis Chia-Hui\n  | year = 2017\n  | title = Architectural Theorisations and Phenomena in Asia: The Polychronotypic Jetztzeit\n  | publisher = Springer\n  | isbn = 978-3-319-58433-1\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Arokiasamy\n  | first = Christina\n  | year = 2017\n  | title = The Malaysian Kitchen: 150 Recipes for Simple Home Cooking\n  | publisher = HMH Books\n  | isbn = 978-0-544-81002-0\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ma\n  | first = Hailong\n  | year = 2017\n  | title = The History of Chinese Muslims' Migration into Malaysia\n  | publisher = King Faisal Center for Research and Islamic Studies (KFCRIS)\n  | isbn = 978-603-8206-48-5\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Tyson\n  | first = Adam\n  | year = 2018\n  | title = The Political Economy of Brain Drain and Talent Capture: Evidence from Malaysia and Singapore\n  | publisher = Taylor & Francis\n  | isbn = 978-0-429-77316-7\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Tan\n  | first = Chee Beng\n  | year = 2018\n  | title = Chinese Religion in Malaysia: Temples and Communities\n  | publisher = BRILL\n  | isbn = 978-90-04-35787-7\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Wade\n  | first1 = Geoff\n  | last2 = Chin\n  | first2 = James K.\n  | year = 2018\n  | title = China and Southeast Asia: Historical Interactions\n  | publisher = Taylor & Francis\n  | isbn = 978-0-429-95212-8\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Zhang\n  | first = Quan\n  | year = 2018\n  | title = Pacific Rim Objective Measurement Symposium (PROMS) 2016 Conference Proceedings: Rasch and the Future\n  | publisher = Springer Singapore\n  | isbn = 978-981-10-8138-5\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Dayley\n  | first = Robert\n  | year = 2018\n  | title = Southeast Asia in the New International Era\n  | publisher = Taylor & Francis\n  | isbn = 978-0-429-97424-3\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|author=Sharon A. Carstens|title=Histories, Cultures, Identities: Studies in Malaysian Chinese Worlds|year=2005|publisher=NUS Press|isbn=978-9971-69-312-1}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Teong Jin|last1=Tan|first2=Wah Foon|last2=Ho|first3=Joo Lan|last3=Tan|title=The Chinese Malaysian contribution|year=2005|publisher=Centre for Malaysian Chinese Studies|isbn=978-983-9673-95-1}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Rita|last=Sim|title=Unmistakably Chinese, Genuinely Malaysian|year=2012|publisher=Centre for Strategic Engagement|isbn=978-967-10773-0-6}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Chan|first=Rachel Suet Kay|url=http://www.mcser.org/journal/index.php/ajis/article/view/876/907|title=The Impact of Cultural Globalisation on Identity Formation among the Malaysian Chinese|year=2013|journal=Academic Journal of Interdisciplinary Studies|volume=2|number=9}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Malaysia}}\n{{Overseas Chinese}}\n\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Chinese descent| ]]\n[[Category:Chinese diaspora by country|Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Chinese diaspora in Malaysia| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Malaysia|Chinese]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Sabah|Chinese]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Sarawak|Chinese]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Malaysia]]\n[[Category:China\u2013Malaysia relations]]\n", "name_user": "Gandalfett", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malaysian_Chinese"}
{"title_page": "Cell cycle analysis", "text_new": "'''Cell cycle analysis by DNA content measurement''' is a method that most frequently employs [[flow cytometry]] to distinguish cells in different phases of the [[cell cycle]]. Before analysis, the cells are usually [[wiktionary:Permeabilization|permeabilised]] and treated with a [[fluorescent dye]] that stains [[DNA]] quantitatively, such as [[propidium iodide]] (PI) or 4,6-diamidino-2-phenylindole (DAPI). The fluorescence intensity of the stained cells correlates with the amount of DNA they contain. As the DNA content doubles during the [[S phase]], the DNA content (and thereby intensity of fluorescence) of cells in the [[G0 phase|G<sub>0</sub> phase]] and [[G1 phase|G<sub>1</sub> phase]] (before S), in the S phase, and in the [[G2 phase|G<sub>2</sub> phase]] and [[M phase]] (after S) identifies the cell cycle phase position in the major phases (G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> versus S versus G<sub>2</sub>/M phase) of the cell cycle. The cellular DNA content of individual cells is often plotted as their frequency histogram to provide information about relative frequency (percentage) of cells in the major phases of the cell cycle.\n\nCell cycle anomalies revealed on the DNA content frequency histogram are often observed after different types of cell damage, for example such [[DNA damage]] that interrupts the cell cycle progression at certain [[cell cycle checkpoint|checkpoints]]. Such an arrest of the cell cycle progression can lead either to an effective DNA repair, which may prevent transformation of normal into a cancer cell ([[carcinogenesis]]), or to cell death, often by the mode of [[apoptosis]]. An arrest of cells in G<sub>0</sub> or G<sub>1</sub> is often seen as a result of lack of nutrients (growth factors), for example after [[blood serum|serum]] deprivation.\nCell cycle analysis was first described in 1969 at [[Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory]] by a group from the [[University of California]] using the [[Feulgen stain]]ing technique.<ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Van Dilla MA, Trujillo TT, Mullaney PF, Coulter JR | date        = 14 March 1969\n| title       = Cell Microfluorometry: A Method for Rapid Fluorescence Measurement\n| journal     = [[Science (journal)|Science]]\n| volume      = 163\n| issue       = 3872\n| pages       = 1213\u20131214\n| pmid        = 5812751\n| doi         = 10.1126/science.163.3872.1213\n}}\n</ref> The first protocol for cell cycle analysis using propidium iodide staining was presented in 1975 by [[Awtar Krishan]] from [[Harvard Medical School]] and is still widely cited today.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| author      = Krishan A.\n| date        = July 1975\n| title       = Rapid flow cytofluorometric analysis of mammalian cell cycle by propidium iodide staining\n| journal     = [[The Journal of Cell Biology]]\n| volume      = 66\n| issue       = 1\n| pages       = 188\u2013193\n| pmid        = 49354\n| doi         = 10.1083/jcb.66.1.188\n| pmc      = 2109516\n}}\n</ref>\n\n'''Multiparameter analysis of the cell cycle''' includes, in addition to measurement of cellular DNA content, other cell cycle related constituents/features. The concurrent measurement of cellular DNA and RNA content, or DNA susceptibility to denaturation at low pH using the metachromatic dye [[acridine orange]], reveals the G<sub>1Q</sub>, G<sub>1A</sub>, and G<sub>1B</sub> cell cycle compartments and also makes it possible to discriminate between S, G<sub>2</sub> and mitotic cells.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Darzynkiewicz Z, Traganos F, Melamed MR | year = 1980 | title = New cell cycle compartments identified by multiparameter [[flow cytometry]] | journal = Cytometry | volume = 1 | issue = 11| pages = 98\u2013108 | pmid = 6161370 | pmc = 350355 }}</ref> The cells in G<sub>1Q</sub> are quiescent, temporarily withdrawn from the cell cycle (also identifiable as G<sub>0</sub>), the G<sub>1A</sub> are in the growth phase while G<sub>1B</sub> are the cells just prior entering S, with their growth (RNA and protein content, size) similar to that of the cells initiating DNA replication. Similar cell cycle compartments are also recognized by multiparameter analysis that includes measurement of expression of [[cyclin D1]], [[cyclin E]], [[cyclin A]] and [[cyclin B1]], each in relation to DNA content <ref>Darzynkiewicz Z, Gong JP, Juan G, Ardelt B, Traganos, F. (1996) Cytometry of cyclin proteins ''Cytometry'' 25:1-13, PMID 8875049 {{doi|10.1002/(SICI)1097-0320(19960901)25:1<1::AID-CYTO1>3.0.CO;2-N}}</ref> Concurrent measurement of DNA content and of incorporation of DNA precursor [[5-bromo-2'-deoxyuridine]] (BrdU) by flow cytometry is an especially useful assay, that has been widely used in analysis of the cell cycle in vitro and in vivo.<ref>Gray JW, Dolbeare F, Pallavicini MG, Beisker W, Waldman F. (1986) Cell cycle analysis using flow cytometry. ''Int J Radiat Biol Relat Stud Phys Chem Med.'' Feb;49(2):237-55. {{PMID|3510993}}.</ref> However, the incorporation of [[5-ethynyl-2'-deoxyuridine]] (EdU), the precursor whose detection offers certain advantages over BrdU, has now become the preferred methodology do detect DNA replicating (S-phase) cells.<ref>Buck SB, Bradford J, Gee KR, Agnew BJ, Clarke ST, Salic A. (2008) Detection of S-phase cell cycle progression using 5-ethynyl-2'-deoxyuridine incorporation with click chemistry, an alternative to using 5-bromo-2'-deoxyuridine antibodies. ''Biotechniques'' Jun;44(7):927-9. doi: 10.2144/000112812. {{PMID|18533904}}</ref>\n\n==Experimental procedure==\n\n[[File:1D30 DNA DAPI.png|250px|right|thumb|DAPI (magenta) bound to the minor groove of DNA (green and blue). From {{PDB|1D30}}.]] Unless staining is performed using [[Hoechst 33342]], the first step in preparing cells for cell cycle analysis is permeabilisation of the cells' [[plasma membrane]]s. This is usually done by incubating them in a [[buffer solution]] containing a mild [[detergent]]<ref>\n{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Vindel\u00f8v LL, Christensen IJ, Nissen NI | date        = March 1983\n| title       = A detergent-trypsin method for the preparation of nuclei for flow cytometric DNA analysis\n| journal     = [[Cytometry (journal)|Cytometry]]\n| volume      = 3\n| issue       = 5\n| pages       = 323\u2013327\n| pmid        = 6188586\n| doi         = 10.1002/cyto.990030503\n}}\n</ref> such as [[Triton X-100]] or [[NP-40]], or by [[Fixation (histology)|fixating]] them in [[ethanol]]. Most fluorescent DNA dyes (one of exceptions is [[Hoechst 33342]]) are not plasma membrane permeant, that is, unable to pass through an intact cell membrane. Permeabilisation is therefore crucial for the success of the next step, the staining of the cells.\n\nPrior to (or during the staining step) the cells are often treated with [[RNase A]] to remove [[RNA]]s. This is important because \ncertain dyes that stain DNA will also stain RNA, thus creating [[Artifact (error)|artefact]]s that would distort the results. An exception is the metachromatic fluorochrome [[acridine orange]],  which under the specific staining protocol can differentially stain both, RNA (generating red luminescence) and DNA (green fluorescence), or in another protocol, after removal of RNA and partial DNA denaturation, to differentially stain double-stranded DNA (green fluorescence) versus single-stranded DNA(red luminescence)<sup>[3]</sup>. Aside from propidium iodide and acridine orange, quantifiable dyes that are frequently used include (but are not limited to) DRAQ5, [[7-Aminoactinomycin D]], [[DAPI]] and [[Hoechst 33342]].\n\n===Doublet discrimination===\n\nSince cells and especially fixed cells tend to stick together, cell aggregates have to be excluded from analysis through a process called ''doublet discrimination''. This is important because a doublet of two G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> cells has the same total content of DNA and thus the same fluorescence intensity as a single G<sub>2</sub>/M cell.<ref>Sharpless T, Traganos F, Darzynkiewicz Z, Melamed MR. (1975) Flow cytofluorimetry: discrimination between single cells and cell aggregates by direct size measurements. Acta Cytol. 19(6):577-81. {{PMID|1108568}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Wersto RP, Chrest FJ, Leary JF, Morris C, Stetler-Stevenson MA, Gabrielson E | date        = 15 October 2001\n| title       = Doublet discrimination in DNA cell-cycle analysis\n| journal     = Cytometry\n| volume      = 46\n| issue       = 5\n| pages       = 296\u2013306\n| pmid        = 11746105\n| doi         = 10.1002/cyto.1171\n}}</ref> Unless recognized as such the G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> doublets would contribute to [[false positive]] identification and count of G<sub>2</sub>/M cells.\n\n==Related methods==\n\n===Nicoletti assay===\n\nThe '''Nicoletti assay''', named after its inventor, the Italian physician [[Ildo Nicoletti]], is a modified form of cell cycle analysis. It is used to detect and quantify [[apoptosis]], a form of [[programmed cell death]], by analysing cells with a DNA content less than 2n (\"sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> cells\"). Such cells are usually the result of [[apoptotic DNA fragmentation]]: during apoptosis, the DNA is degraded by cellular [[endonuclease]]s. Therefore, [[Cell nucleus|nuclei]] of apoptotic cells contain less DNA than nuclei of healthy G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> cells, resulting in a sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak in the fluorescence [[histogram]] that can be used to determine the relative amount of apoptotic cells in a sample.This method was developed and first described in 1991 by Nicoletti and co-workers at [[University of Perugia|Perugia University]] School of Medicine.<ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Nicoletti I, Migliorati G, Pagliacci MC, Grignani F, Riccardi C | date        = 3 June 1991\n| title       = A rapid and simple method for measuring thymocyte apoptosis by propidium iodide staining and flow cytometry\n| journal     = [[Journal of Immunological Methods]]\n| volume      = 139\n| issue       = 2\n| pages       = 271\u2013279\n| pmid        = 1710634\n| doi         = 10.1016/0022-1759(91)90198-O}}</ref> An optimised protocol developed by two of the authors of the original publication was published in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Riccardi C, Nicoletti I | date        = 9 November 2006\n| title       = Analysis of apoptosis by propidium iodide staining and flow cytometry\n| journal     = [[Nature Protocols]]\n| volume      = 1\n| issue       = 3\n| pages       = 1458\u20131461\n| pmid        = 17406435\n| doi         = 10.1038/nprot.2006.238}}</ref> The objects measured within the sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak, with DNA content  lesser than 5% of that of the G<sub>0</sub>G<sub>1</sub> peak, in all probability are apoptotic bodies and thus do not represent individual apoptotic cells <ref>Darzynkiewicz Z, Bedner E, Traganos F. (2001) Difficulties and pitfalls in analysis of apoptosis.  Methods Cell Biol 63:527-559,  {{PMID|11060857}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Nicoletti assay with healthy (left) and apoptotic (middle and right) cells\n|width=259\n|height=170\n|lines=3\n|align=center\n|File:Nicoletti assay 1.png|alt1=|Healthy cells. Note the absence of a  sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak.\n|File:Nicoletti assay 2.png|alt2=|Apoptotic cells one day after apoptosis induction. Note the presence of a sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak.\n|File:Nicoletti assay 3.png|alt3=|Apoptotic cells several days after apoptosis induction. Note the relative increase of the sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak.}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/wibr/services/docs/cellcyc.pdf \n |title=Cell Cycle Basics \n |accessdate=2010-05-20 \n |publisher=University College London \n |format=PDF, 0.1 MB \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606092908/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/wibr/services/docs/cellcyc.pdf \n |archivedate=2011-06-06 \n}}\n*{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.phnxflow.com/Introduction%20to%20Cell%20Cycle%20Analysis.pdf\n| author     = Rabinovitch, Peter\n| title      = Introduction to Cell Cycle Analysis\n| accessdate = 2010-05-20\n| publisher  = Phoenix Flow Systems, Inc.\n| format     = PDF, 0.5 MB}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.phiab.se/applications/cell-division \n |title=Label-free Cell Cycle Analysis \n |accessdate=2013-07-28 \n |publisher=Phase Holographic Imaging AB \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629210808/http://www.phiab.se/applications/cell-division \n |archivedate=2013-06-29 \n}}\n\n[[Category:Biological techniques and tools]]\n[[Category:Cell biology]]\n[[Category:Cell cycle]]\n[[Category:Flow cytometry]]\n", "text_old": "'''Cell cycle analysis by DNA content measurement''' is a method that most frequently employs [[flow cytometry]] to distinguish cells in different phases of the [[cell cycle]]. Before analysis, the cells are usually [[wiktionary:Permeabilization|permeabilised]] and treated with a [[fluorescent dye]] that stains [[DNA]] quantitatively, such as [[propidium iodide]] (PI) or 4,6-diamidino-2-phenylindole (DAPI). The fluorescence intensity of the stained cells correlates with the amount of DNA they contain. As the DNA content doubles during the [[S phase]], the DNA content (and thereby intensity of fluorescence) of cells in the [[G0 phase|G<sub>0</sub> phase]] and [[G1 phase|G<sub>1</sub> phase]] (before S), in the S phase, and in the [[G2 phase|G<sub>2</sub> phase]] and [[M phase]] (after S) identifies the cell cycle phase position in the major phases (G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> versus S versus G<sub>2</sub>/M phase) of the cell cycle. The cellular DNA content of individual cells is often plotted as their frequency histogram to provide information about relative frequency (percentage) of cells in the major phases of the cell cycle.\n\nCell cycle anomalies revealed on the DNA content frequency histogram are often observed after different types of cell damage, for example such [[DNA damage]] that interrupts the cell cycle progression at certain [[cell cycle checkpoint|checkpoints]]. Such an arrest of the cell cycle progression can lead either to an effective DNA repair, which may prevent transformation of normal into a cancer cell ([[carcinogenesis]]), or to cell death, often by the mode of [[apoptosis]]. An arrest of cells in G<sub>0</sub> or G<sub>1</sub> is often seen as a result of lack of nutrients (growth factors), for example after [[blood serum|serum]] deprivation.\nCell cycle analysis was first described in 1969 at [[Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory]] by a group from the [[University of California]] using the [[Feulgen stain]]ing technique.<ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Van Dilla MA, Trujillo TT, Mullaney PF, Coulter JR | date        = 14 March 1969\n| title       = Cell Microfluorometry: A Method for Rapid Fluorescence Measurement\n| journal     = [[Science (journal)|Science]]\n| volume      = 163\n| issue       = 3872\n| pages       = 1213\u20131214\n| pmid        = 5812751\n| doi         = 10.1126/science.163.3872.1213\n}}\n</ref> The first protocol for cell cycle analysis using propidium iodide staining was presented in 1975 by [[Awtar Krishan]] from [[Harvard Medical School]] and is still widely cited today.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| author      = Krishan A.\n| date        = July 1975\n| title       = Rapid flow cytofluorometric analysis of mammalian cell cycle by propidium iodide staining\n| journal     = [[The Journal of Cell Biology]]\n| volume      = 66\n| issue       = 1\n| pages       = 188\u2013193\n| pmid        = 49354\n| doi         = 10.1083/jcb.66.1.188\n| pmc      = 2109516\n}}\n</ref>\n\n'''Multiparameter analysis of the cell cycle''' includes, in addition to measurement of cellular DNA content, other cell cycle related constituents/features. The concurrent measurement of cellular DNA and RNA content, or DNA susceptibility to denaturation at low pH using the metachromatic dye [[acridine orange]], reveals the G<sub>1Q</sub>, G<sub>1A</sub>, and G<sub>1B</sub> cell cycle compartments and also makes it possible to discriminate between S, G<sub>2</sub> and mitotic cells.<ref>Darzynkiewicz Z, Traganos F, Melamed MR. (1980) New cell cycle compartments identified by multiparameter [[flow cytometry]]. Cytometry 1:98-108. {{PMID|6161370}}</ref> The cells in G<sub>1Q</sub> are quiescent, temporarily withdrawn from the cell cycle (also identifiable as G<sub>0</sub>), the G<sub>1A</sub> are in the growth phase while G<sub>1B</sub> are the cells just prior entering S, with their growth (RNA and protein content, size) similar to that of the cells initiating DNA replication. Similar cell cycle compartments are also recognized by multiparameter analysis that includes measurement of expression of [[cyclin D1]], [[cyclin E]], [[cyclin A]] and [[cyclin B1]], each in relation to DNA content <ref>Darzynkiewicz Z, Gong JP, Juan G, Ardelt B, Traganos, F. (1996) Cytometry of cyclin proteins. Cytometry 25:1-13, {{PMID|8875049}} {{doi|10.1002/(SICI)1097-0320(19960901)25:1<1::AID-CYTO1>3.0.CO;2-N}}</ref> Concurrent measurement of DNA content and of incorporation of DNA precursor [[5-bromo-2'-deoxyuridine]] (BrdU) by flow cytometry is an especially useful assay, that has been widely used in analysis of the cell cycle in vitro and in vivo.<ref>Gray JW, Dolbeare F, Pallavicini MG, Beisker W, Waldman F. (1986) Cell cycle analysis using flow cytometry. Int J Radiat Biol Relat Stud Phys Chem Med. Feb;49(2):237-55. {{PMID|3510993}}.</ref> However, the incorporation of [[5-ethynyl-2'-deoxyuridine]] (EdU), the precursor whose detection offers certain advantages over BrdU, has now become the preferred methodology do detect DNA replicating (S-phase) cells.<ref>Buck SB, Bradford J, Gee KR, Agnew BJ, Clarke ST, Salic A. (2008) Detection of S-phase cell cycle progression using 5-ethynyl-2'-deoxyuridine incorporation with click chemistry, an alternative to using 5-bromo-2'-deoxyuridine antibodies. Biotechniques. Jun;44(7):927-9. doi: 10.2144/000112812. {{PMID|18533904}}</ref>\n\n==Experimental procedure==\n\n[[File:1D30 DNA DAPI.png|250px|right|thumb|DAPI (magenta) bound to the minor groove of DNA (green and blue). From {{PDB|1D30}}.]] Unless staining is performed using [[Hoechst 33342]], the first step in preparing cells for cell cycle analysis is permeabilisation of the cells' [[plasma membrane]]s. This is usually done by incubating them in a [[buffer solution]] containing a mild [[detergent]]<ref>\n{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Vindel\u00f8v LL, Christensen IJ, Nissen NI | date        = March 1983\n| title       = A detergent-trypsin method for the preparation of nuclei for flow cytometric DNA analysis\n| journal     = [[Cytometry (journal)|Cytometry]]\n| volume      = 3\n| issue       = 5\n| pages       = 323\u2013327\n| pmid        = 6188586\n| doi         = 10.1002/cyto.990030503\n}}\n</ref> such as [[Triton X-100]] or [[NP-40]], or by [[Fixation (histology)|fixating]] them in [[ethanol]]. Most fluorescent DNA dyes (one of exceptions is [[Hoechst 33342]]) are not plasma membrane permeant, that is, unable to pass through an intact cell membrane. Permeabilisation is therefore crucial for the success of the next step, the staining of the cells.\n\nPrior to (or during the staining step) the cells are often treated with [[RNase A]] to remove [[RNA]]s. This is important because \ncertain dyes that stain DNA will also stain RNA, thus creating [[Artifact (error)|artefact]]s that would distort the results. An exception is the metachromatic fluorochrome [[acridine orange]],  which under the specific staining protocol can differentially stain both, RNA (generating red luminescence) and DNA (green fluorescence), or in another protocol, after removal of RNA and partial DNA denaturation, to differentially stain double-stranded DNA (green fluorescence) versus single-stranded DNA(red luminescence)<sup>[3]</sup>. Aside from propidium iodide and acridine orange, quantifiable dyes that are frequently used include (but are not limited to) DRAQ5, [[7-Aminoactinomycin D]], [[DAPI]] and [[Hoechst 33342]].\n\n===Doublet discrimination===\n\nSince cells and especially fixed cells tend to stick together, cell aggregates have to be excluded from analysis through a process called ''doublet discrimination''. This is important because a doublet of two G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> cells has the same total content of DNA and thus the same fluorescence intensity as a single G<sub>2</sub>/M cell.<ref>Sharpless T, Traganos F, Darzynkiewicz Z, Melamed MR. (1975) Flow cytofluorimetry: discrimination between single cells and cell aggregates by direct size measurements. Acta Cytol. 19(6):577-81. {{PMID|1108568}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Wersto RP, Chrest FJ, Leary JF, Morris C, Stetler-Stevenson MA, Gabrielson E | date        = 15 October 2001\n| title       = Doublet discrimination in DNA cell-cycle analysis\n| journal     = Cytometry\n| volume      = 46\n| issue       = 5\n| pages       = 296\u2013306\n| pmid        = 11746105\n| doi         = 10.1002/cyto.1171\n}}</ref> Unless recognized as such the G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> doublets would contribute to [[false positive]] identification and count of G<sub>2</sub>/M cells.\n\n==Related methods==\n\n===Nicoletti assay===\n\nThe '''Nicoletti assay''', named after its inventor, the Italian physician [[Ildo Nicoletti]], is a modified form of cell cycle analysis. It is used to detect and quantify [[apoptosis]], a form of [[programmed cell death]], by analysing cells with a DNA content less than 2n (\"sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> cells\"). Such cells are usually the result of [[apoptotic DNA fragmentation]]: during apoptosis, the DNA is degraded by cellular [[endonuclease]]s. Therefore, [[Cell nucleus|nuclei]] of apoptotic cells contain less DNA than nuclei of healthy G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> cells, resulting in a sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak in the fluorescence [[histogram]] that can be used to determine the relative amount of apoptotic cells in a sample.This method was developed and first described in 1991 by Nicoletti and co-workers at [[University of Perugia|Perugia University]] School of Medicine.<ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Nicoletti I, Migliorati G, Pagliacci MC, Grignani F, Riccardi C | date        = 3 June 1991\n| title       = A rapid and simple method for measuring thymocyte apoptosis by propidium iodide staining and flow cytometry\n| journal     = [[Journal of Immunological Methods]]\n| volume      = 139\n| issue       = 2\n| pages       = 271\u2013279\n| pmid        = 1710634\n| doi         = 10.1016/0022-1759(91)90198-O}}</ref> An optimised protocol developed by two of the authors of the original publication was published in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal\n|vauthors=Riccardi C, Nicoletti I | date        = 9 November 2006\n| title       = Analysis of apoptosis by propidium iodide staining and flow cytometry\n| journal     = [[Nature Protocols]]\n| volume      = 1\n| issue       = 3\n| pages       = 1458\u20131461\n| pmid        = 17406435\n| doi         = 10.1038/nprot.2006.238}}</ref> The objects measured within the sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak, with DNA content  lesser than 5% of that of the G<sub>0</sub>G<sub>1</sub> peak, in all probability are apoptotic bodies and thus do not represent individual apoptotic cells <ref>Darzynkiewicz Z, Bedner E, Traganos F. (2001) Difficulties and pitfalls in analysis of apoptosis.  Methods Cell Biol 63:527-559,  {{PMID|11060857}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Nicoletti assay with healthy (left) and apoptotic (middle and right) cells\n|width=259\n|height=170\n|lines=3\n|align=center\n|File:Nicoletti assay 1.png|alt1=|Healthy cells. Note the absence of a  sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak.\n|File:Nicoletti assay 2.png|alt2=|Apoptotic cells one day after apoptosis induction. Note the presence of a sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak.\n|File:Nicoletti assay 3.png|alt3=|Apoptotic cells several days after apoptosis induction. Note the relative increase of the sub-G<sub>0</sub>/G<sub>1</sub> peak.}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/wibr/services/docs/cellcyc.pdf \n |title=Cell Cycle Basics \n |accessdate=2010-05-20 \n |publisher=University College London \n |format=PDF, 0.1 MB \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606092908/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/wibr/services/docs/cellcyc.pdf \n |archivedate=2011-06-06 \n}}\n*{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.phnxflow.com/Introduction%20to%20Cell%20Cycle%20Analysis.pdf\n| author     = Rabinovitch, Peter\n| title      = Introduction to Cell Cycle Analysis\n| accessdate = 2010-05-20\n| publisher  = Phoenix Flow Systems, Inc.\n| format     = PDF, 0.5 MB}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.phiab.se/applications/cell-division \n |title=Label-free Cell Cycle Analysis \n |accessdate=2013-07-28 \n |publisher=Phase Holographic Imaging AB \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629210808/http://www.phiab.se/applications/cell-division \n |archivedate=2013-06-29 \n}}\n\n[[Category:Biological techniques and tools]]\n[[Category:Cell biology]]\n[[Category:Cell cycle]]\n[[Category:Flow cytometry]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:, added 1 PMC, templated 1 journal cites, added 1 issue number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_cycle_analysis"}
